<HEADLINE> US Trade Deficit Down Sharply to 8.5 Bln Dlrs in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Commerce Department
announced today that the U.S. trade deficit declined sharply in
March to 8.5 billion U.S. dollars as the country's exports hit an
all-time high.
</P>
<P>
The department said in its monthly report that the deficit in
goods and services was the lowest it has been since last November
and took a big-margin drop of 19.3 percent from an imbalance of
10.5 billion dollars in February.
</P>
<P>
Exports of U.S. goods and services climbed up to a record 76.5
billion dollars in March as compared with 73.5 billion dollars in
the previous month. Meanwhile, imports also rose to a record,
surging to 85 billion dollars from February's 84 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The deficit with Japan was up in March by 8.3 percent to 4.6
billion dollars, the highest since last November, due to increased
imports of Japanese computers and telephone equipment.
</P>
<P>
For March, the deficit with Mexico rose 23.2 percent to 1.5
billion dollars, the worst showing since last November. The
deficit with Canada was down 13.5 percent to 1.3 billion dollars.
U.S. exports to Canada and imports from that country were both at
the highest levels ever recorded by the United States in trade
with any country.
</P>
<P>
U.S. exports to all of Central and South America rose to a
record 5.2 billion dollars in March.
</P>
<P>
America's foreign oil bill edged up a slight 0.3 percent in
March to 5.3 billion dollars as a 13 percent jump in volume was
offset by a decline in price. Crude oil prices dropped to an
average of 18.72 dollars per barrel, down from 20.49 dollars in
February.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department suffered a major embarrassment last
month when it initially overstated the February deficit by 1.2
billion dollars as a result of incorrectly mixed old oil reports
into the February report.
</P>
<P>
Even with the improvement in March, the trade deficit in the
first three months of this year has been running at an annual rate
of 125.5 billion dollars, a deterioration from last year's total
deficit of 114.3 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
