<HEADLINE> S. Africa Donates Money to UNDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The South African government
has made a voluntary pledge of 885,000 Rands (201,136 U.S.
dollars) to the United Nations Development Program (UNDP), the
Foreign Affairs Deparment said today.
</P>
<P>
The contribution would be used to cover costs of programs
administered by the UNDP in South Africa, the department
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, South Africa had contributed 100,000 Rands
(22,727 U.S. dollars) to the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees for UN operations in Rwanda and 600,000 Rands (136,364
U.S. dollars) for re-settling Angolan refugees.
</P>
<P>
Pretoria had also donated 150,000 Rands (34,090 U.S. dollars)
to the UN Department of Humanitarian Affairs towards the Malawi
and Mozambican floods, the officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
