<HEADLINE> France Urges Zaire's New Leaders to Hold Free Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- France has presented a four-point
message to Zaire's new authorities under Laurent Kabila, calling
for free elections and protection of French nationals in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
It follows the assassination of two French businessmen in
Kinshasa on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The French government decided on the message at a meeting
chaired by President Jacques Chirac this morning, said French
Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
In the message, France urged the new authorities in Zaire to
"conform themselves with the rules of democracy," and asked them
to "organize, very rapidly, free elections, observed by the
international community."
</P>
<P>
While expressing sorrow over the assassination of two
Frenchmen, France "demands very firmly that measures be taken for
assuring the security of the French community" in Zaire, the
spokesman quoted from the message.
</P>
<P>
Michel Tournaire and Herve Riguaud, two French businessmen who
had long lived in Zaire, were killed by two gunmen wearing
military uniforms at a factory near central Kinshasa, under
circumstances which are as yet unclear.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Herve de Charette said today in a radio
interview that he did not think the assassination was a
retaliation over French policy towards Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The government also expressed deep worry over the plight of
Rwandan refugees and displaced people in Zaire, and urged the new
leaders of Kinshasa to guarantee security on the borders between
Zaire and its neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
France was apparently referring to Zaire's borders with
neighboring Congo and the Central African Republic, two countries
which have supported President Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
The French ambassador in Kinshasa, Michel Rougagnou, will "make
contact with the new authorities of the Democratic Republic of
Congo, at the highest level", said Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
De Charette also expressed shock over what he called the
"indifference" of the international community over the situation
of Rwandan refugees in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"Thousands and thousands of men, women and children have been
abandoned. There is an international inquiry which was demanded by
the United Nations, and I say here that the U.N. cannot today
accomplish its work in the field," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The international humanitarian group Medecins sans Frontieres
said on Monday that 190,000 Hutu refugees had disappeared from
eastern Zaire over the past several months.
</P>
<P>
"The latest reports which we have received are extremely
worrying. We ask instantly that the non-governmental organizations
as well as an envoy of the United Nations can go into the field
and investigate immediately," said Rummelhardt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
