<HEADLINE> Tonkov Wins Fifth Stage in Giro d'Italia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Pavel Tonkov beat
Luc Leblanc and Marco Pantani in a four-way sprint in the first
tough mountainous stage of the Giro d'Italia on Wednesday,
retaining the pink jersey and strengthening his overall lead.
</P>
<P>
Tonkov's fifth-stage victory put considerable distance between
himself and most of his main rivals, who finished well behind in
the leg which ended at Terminello peak, 1,675 meters above sea
level after a final 15-kilometer climb.
</P>
<P>
Russian Eugeni Berzin, the 1994 Giro champion and the main
rival of the 28-year-old Tonkov, trailed by more than five
minutes, possibly compromising his chances to win the 22-stage
marathon.
</P>
<P>
Most cyclists failed on the final climb to Terminillo,
northeast of Rome, after the 215-kilometer stage from Arezzo, in
Tuscany, was marred by rain. Leblanc rushed ahead 200 meters from
the finish line but Tonkov was quick to respond and overtake him.
</P>
<P>
The second-place finish moved the Frenchman from fourth to
second place overall.
</P>
<P>
The Tour of Italy, which ends in Milan on June 8, continues
Thursday with a 210-kilometer hilly stage from Rieti to Lanciano.
</P>
</TEXT>
