<HEADLINE> Balanced-Budget Plan Narrowly Passes US House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives decisively approved a balanced budget agreement
early today after a marathon debate, narrowly defeating a proposal
to boost highway spending that could have disrupted the accord.
</P>
<P>
By a vote of 333 to 99 a few hours before dawn, the House
approved the plan to balance the federal budget by 2002 which was
reached on May 2 by the Clinton administration and the Republican
leaders in the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
Critics of the agreement said that the package gives tax breaks
to the wealthy and neglects programs to help children and rebuild
highways and bridges. They proposed a move to add 12 billion
dollars to the 125-billion-dollar plan in highway spending already
contained in the balanced-budget agreement.
</P>
<P>
Pleas from the White House and Republican leaders helped turn
away a surprisingly strong challenge to amend the pact by
increasing transportation spending.
</P>
<P>
The Republican leadership and the White House launched an
intense campaign in the past few days to defeat an amendment to
boost spending on highway projects.
</P>
<P>
It was the first substantial political test of an agreement
that seeks a balanced budget by 2002 as well as 85 billion dollars
in net tax cuts and a reduction of 115 billion dollars in Medicare
spending.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the balanced-budget agreement will also meet with
strong opposition in the U.S. Senate. Another significant change
proposed to amend the agreement would boost cigarette taxes to
expand health coverage for uninsured children and further cut the
budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
By raising the cigarette tax by 43 cents a pack, the proposal
would raise 20 billion dollars for children's insurance and 10
billion to reduce the deficit.
</P>
<P>
The strong opposition to the balanced-budget agreement, mainly
from Democrats in the U.S. Congress, is a clear evidence that
there is a deep gap between the two parties on the pact. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
