<HEADLINE> Mobutu Followers Leave for Chad to Seek Asylum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of followers of Zaire's ousted
president Mobutu Sese Seko left the Togolese capital of Lome today
for Chad, whose government has agreed to receive them, the Agence
France-Presse (AFP) news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu will also go to Chad as soon as his health allows him
to do so, AFP quoted reliable sources in Lome as saying.
</P>
<P>
Two aircraft, including one of the Congolese air company Lima
Congo, transported about 85 members of Mobutu's followers to
Ndjamena, the capital of Chad, from Lome, where they were refused
entry by the local authorities, said Togolese officials.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu has been housed in the presidential palace of Lome for
"humanitarian reason" since he fled there Sunday morning, Togolese
Foreign Minister Koffi Panou said.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu, who was in power for more than 30 years, was forced to
flee into exile after the forces led by Laurent Kabila entered
Kinshasa, Zaire's capital.
</P>
<P>
Kabila proclaimed himself president of the country whose name
he changed to "the Democratic Republic of Congo."
</P>
<P>
Kabila flew to Kinshasa Tuesday from his southern stronghold of
Lubumbashi to form an interim government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
