<HEADLINE> US Plans to Pay Off UN Dues Stalls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration's
proposal to pay 1 billion U.S. dollars dues it owed to the United
nations has stalled in Congress, the New York Times reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Republicans are insisting on paying only some of the debt, over
a longer stretch of time and only after the U.N. agrees to a
series of demands, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. owed the U.N. more than 15 billion U.S. dollars and
remains the largest debtor among the U.N. members. Earlier this
year, President Bill Clinton promised to pay the debt.
</P>
<P>
Proposals circulating in the House and the Senate raised a
series of conditions for paying the arrears, including a reduction
of Washington's annual dues, and more reforms in the U.N., the
report said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to say it loud and clear: the arrears will be paid
only when the reforms are made," it quoted one senator as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The administration, in quiet negotiations with Republican
leaders, has opposed many of the conditions," it added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been widely criticized by many countries,
including its allies, for not paying its U.N. dues in time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
