<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British officials, Sinn Fein Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Irish Republican Army's (IRA)
political wing Sinn Fein and British officials began talks today
on the Northern Ireland peace process, the first such meeting
since the IRA ended its ceasefire in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, in the Ulster capital of Belfast, was between
Martin McGuinness, chief negotiator for Sinn Fein, and civil
servants.
</P>
<P>
"From our point of view in Sinn Fein there is a very strong
desire to break the impasse and to move forward to a fair and just
political settlement on this island," McGuinness told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"You will also appreciate that we are dealing now with a new
British government which has inherited the present situation," he
added.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair offered to ease a ban on
official contact with Sinn Fein last week, putting new life into
the stalled Northern Ireland peace process.
</P>
<P>
The IRA has waged guerrilla war since 1969 to end the British
rule of Northern Ireland and merge it with Ireland proper. But the
60 percent Protestant population in Northern Ireland favors
continued ties with Britain.
</P>
<P>
Although official talks were resumed, Sinn Fein has been barred
by the British government from having a seat in the multi-party
peace talks to be resumed on June 3.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams today urged the British government
to state "with absolute clarity" that Sinn Fein would immediately
be allowed to attend the talks if the IRA called a ceasefire.
</P>
</TEXT>
