<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Remains Second on Competitiveness Ranking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong still holds the second
place in the global competitiveness, a little over a month before
its sovereignty is returned to China, according to a new ranking
issued by the World Economic Forum.
</P>
<P>
The ranking was based on a survey of 3,000 chief executive
officers of big companies of different countries by the
Geneva-based business research organization. Among the 53
economies rated, Singapore again ranks first on the list,
according to the survey. New Zealand gave up its third place to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Our survey indicated that business leaders held the belief
that Hong Kong will maintain its attractiveness and
competitiveness after the transition of sovereignty this year,"
said Frederick Hu, director of the Global Competitiveness Report.
</P>
<P>
China has moved ahead to 29th place from the 36th. But in the
market growth ranking prepared also by the organization, China
moved further ahead from the fourth to the second place.
</P>
<P>
"China still had the world's fastest growing economy last
year, and it attracted more foreign direct investment than any
other country except the U.S.," Hu said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the survey, Jeffrey Sachs, an economist from
Harvard University and a key player in the worldwide survey, said
that there has been mixed progress towards improved economic
competitiveness among the major economies of the world. On the
whole, he said, the state of the world economy is good -- in some
ways better than at any time in recent decades.
</P>
<P>
In nearly all parts of the world, the professor said,
governments have taken important strides to open national
economies to international trade and finance; to get high rates of
inflation under control; and to improve physical infrastructure to
enhance the national economy.
</P>
<P>
But countries in the European Union are laboring under a
chronic fiscal crisis, high unemployment and relatively slow
growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
In Eastern Europe, Russia slipped to the last place from the
49th. Ukraine ranks the 52nd place.
</P>
<P>
The surveyors said that only nine out of the 53 countries and
regions showed even mild concerns over the chances of recession.
The highest likelihood of recession was judged to be in Colombia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
