<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Moves Into 7th in World Competitiveness League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Britain improved its competitiveness
in the past year and now outranks the rest of the European Union,
according to a report published today.
</P>
<P>
The report by the World Economic Forum (WEF) said that the
success of long-term restructuring measures such as privatization
and deregulation had helped Britain make the leap from 15th place
last year.
</P>
<P>
The forum said Britain has recovered from relative economic
decline to become "the envy of continental Europe."
</P>
<P>
Britain's success in overhauling its welfare state, cutting tax
rates, increasing labor market flexibility and achieving sustained
growth with falling unemployment received particular praise.
</P>
<P>
The WEF's annual Global Competitiveness Report seeks to
determine which countries have the greatest ability to achieve
sustained high rates of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The report ranks 53 countries, which are responsible for more
than 90 percent of the world's industrial output, using 153
criteria, ranging from infrastructure and technology through to
business management and regulation.
</P>
<P>
By contrast, it says, continental EU members are suffering "a
chronic crisis of declining competitiveness" caused by rigid labor
markets, burdensome social welfare systems and high levels of
government spending.
</P>
<P>
The forum rates the other EU members only just above Latin
American economies.
</P>
<P>
But the findings were downplayed by Gordon Brown, the
chancellor, who said, "If that were true, I would welcome it."
</P>
<P>
Brown said on BBC Today program, "The accepted indicator of
where we are in the world prosperity league is the OECD, and we
are 21st."
</P>
<P>
"Singapore and Hong Kong were first and second in the table for
the second year running, with the WEF commending the two for their
all-round competitive economies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
