<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Rises to Seventh in Economic Competitiveness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Britain's economic competitiveness
soared to seventh in the world in 1996, from the 15th in the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
It topped the European Union (EU) countries, a report from the
World Economic Forum (WEF) said today.
</P>
<P>
The annual Global Competitiveness Report, surveying 53 better
developed countries on their ability to achieve sustained economic
growth, attributed Britain's leap to its long-term economic
restructuring, including privatization and deregulation.
</P>
<P>
It said Britain was particularly successful in overhauling its
welfare state, cutting tax rates, increasing labor market
flexibility and achieving sustained growth with falling
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
But British Chancellor of Exchequer Gordon Brown played down
the recommendation of the WEF, a Geneva-based non-governmental
annual forum.
</P>
<P>
"If that were true, I would welcome it," Brown said on the BBC
Today program. "The accepted indicator of where we are in the
world prosperity league is the Organization of Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD), and we are the 21st."
</P>
<P>
The report said Britain had recovered from relative economic
decline while most EU members were suffering from "a chronic
crisis of declining competitiveness" resulting from rigid labor
markets, burdensome social welfare systems and high government
spending.
</P>
<P>
Putting the other EU members just above Latin American
economies, the report said Britain had become "the envy of
continental Europe."
</P>
<P>
The survey, using 153 criteria ranging from infrastructure to
business management, covered 53 countries which take more than 90
percent share of the world industrial output.
</P>
<P>
Singapore and Hong Kong ranked first and second in the list,
for the second year running, in their all-round competitiveness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
