<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Prime Minister to Take Tough Action if MP Charged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said today he would take tough action against one of the Labor MPs
if the allegations of bribery against the MP turn out to be true.
</P>
<P>
A newspaper has recently reported that Mohammed Sarwar, who won
a seat in the May 1 general election as Britain's first Moslem MP,
had bribed a rival candidate in the election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Sarwar has admitted giving a 5,000-pound (8,270-dollar) loan to
a candidate in the Glasgow Govan constituency but denied any kind
of bribery. Police are already looking into the allegations
against Sarwar and the Executive set up a three-person committee
to conduct its own investigation.
</P>
<P>
Blair told Labor's National Executive his party had set itself
very high standards.
</P>
<P>
"We did that deliberately, very deliberately, and we must meet
them," an aide quoted Blair as saying at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The claims against 44-year-old Sarwar, a Parkistani-born
millionaire, are the first dark cloud to gather over the new
government, which was helped to its landslide victory in the May 1
election by a number of allegations of financial and sex scandals
against Conservative politicians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
