<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1997 Southern Africa Economic Summit Opens in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A three-day 1997 southern Africa
economic summit started in Harare this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 regional and international business leaders are
attending the summit. They will discuss the regional
integration, trade, infrastructure development, improving the the
region's competitiveness and privatization.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Zimbabwean president Robert Mugabe
said despite southern Africa's political achievements, the region
still shouldered a burden of poverty as the standard of living
was being eroded each year by one percent.
</P>
<P>
He said the fruits of the liberation struggles mounted by the
different countries of the region should be transformed into
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
"In other words, after political security, justice, peace and
democracy, our people still hunger for economic emancipation and
prosperity," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 12 states of the Southern Africa Development Community
(SADC) with a collective population of 140 million have
experienced an economic growth rate of about three percent
annually. But the economic growth rate, matched with a three
percent population growth rate, has been blamed for the one
percent erosion of living standards, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe added,"our political vision for southern Africa is thus
one to create a regional organisational entity which will ensure
increasing living standards for all its citizens under conditions
of peace, political security and democracy."
</P>
<P>
The envisaged regional prosperity should not, however, be
confined to southern Africa, but should be experienced in the
rest of the continent.
</P>
<P>
At the same occasion, South African president Nelson Mandela
emphasised the need for southern African countries to work
together, saying no one country can succeed on its own.
</P>
<P>
He said the region also had to forge a strong partnership with
the international community for it to achieve its economic growth
targets.
</P>
<P>
He also said SADC had to promote partnerships that were
essential to achieving the region's development goals in the
current era.
</P>
<P>
The region, he said, should also place emphasis on the
investment skills and technology and adding value to primary
commodities.
</P>
<P>
Joint ventures between the countries in the region and
developed nations was one best answer for promoting economic
growth in Africa, he said.
</P>
<P>
The summit was convened by the World Economic Forum and SADC.
</P>
<P>
Other regional leaders attending the summit are Zambia's
president Frederick Chiluba and Botswana's president Ketumile
Masire, Swazi prime minister Barnabas Dhlamini and Mozambican
premier Pascoal Mocumbi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
