<HEADLINE> Israeli President Calls for Resuming Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman
today called for a resumption of peace negotiations with Syria so
as to resolve the problems in south Lebanon, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
Weizman told Israel Radio that there were only two options to
solve the problems in Lebanon, either a large military operation,
or serious negotiations with Syria, which has stationed a large
number of troops inside Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli president said "it is time now" to deal with
the problems in south Lebanon, where Israeli troops have
been clashing continuously with the Hezbollah fighters.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "basically the solution is a political
one," which calls for negotiations with the Syrians.
</P>
<P>
Weizman's remarks came amid a marked escalation in fighting
in the Israeli self-declared security zone in south Lebanon
between Israeli troops and Hezbollah fighters.
</P>
<P>
The latest incident occurred today when an Israeli soldier
was seriously wounded in the "security zone" in a roadside
explosion as an Israeli army patrol was passing by.
</P>
<P>
On Monday morning, a suicide bomber of the Amal Movement
attempted to destroy an Israel Navy gunboat; and on the night of
last Thursday, three Israeli paratroopers were killed and seven
wounded in a clash north of the zone.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Labor Party's Member of the
Knesset (Israel's parliament) Yossi Beilin said today that some
senior Israeli army officers in the Northern Command support a
unilateral Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
However, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu has
insisted that the Israeli army not withdraw from Lebanon without
an agreement to prevent Hezbollah from launching raids in the
northern part of Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
