<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Rules Out War With Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean defence minister Moven
Mahachi today ruled out the possibility of a war breaking out
with Zambia over disputed islands along their common border on
the Zambezi river.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Zimbabwe News Agency ZIANA in Nyanga
after officiating at the end of a four-week joint training course
for 250 British and 205 Zimbabwean special army units, Mahachi
said Zimbabwe was optimistic the dispute would be resolved
amicably without resorting to the use of military force.
</P>
<P>
"Zambia is a friendly country to Zimbabwe. We don't think we
can be drawn to war with it. If dispute continues, we will go for
international arbitration but i don't think we will reach that
far because the maps and beacons are there," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "it's just a question of identifying the beacons and
resolve the matter. Our surveyor general's office would be
involved in identifying which islands belong to Zimbabwe and
which ones do not."
</P>
<P>
He said a meeting for security officials from both countries
was held in the Zambian resort town of Livingstone at the weekend
to discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
However, he declined to disclose the outcome of the meeting
but was emphatic that should the dispute persist, Zimbabwe would
opt for international arbitration.
</P>
<P>
He said before seeking international arbitration, the two
countries were trying to resolve the issue through their
ministries of foreign affairs and other related ministries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
