<HEADLINE> Germany's Far-Rightists Vow to Fight Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Germany's leading far-right political
party vowed today to fight the European single currency, the euro,
saying this would be its main election issue in Autumn 1998.
</P>
<P>
Rolf Schlierer, chairman of the Republicans Party, told
reporters in Bonn: "I firmly believe that (the euro) will be the
election issue in 1998". Schlierer said the party was currently
distributing millions of anti-euro brochures.
</P>
<P>
The euro is scheduled to be launched from 1999, and replace the
mark and other European currencies from 2002.
</P>
<P>
The major parties in Bonn, in or out of office, all back the
euro. However, opinion polls have two-thirds of German voters
objecting to giving up the mark for it. 
</P>
