<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Guerrillas Attack Israeli patrol in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Muslim guerrillas today
launched a bombing attack on an Israeli infantry patrol inside the
Israeli-occupied border strip in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Security sources said that at least one Israeli soldier was
wounded in the attack.
</P>
<P>
Guerrillas detonated a roadside bomb near the village of Arnoun
in Nabatiyeh area inside the Israeli self-proclaimed "security
zone," when an Israeli patrol comprising six soldiers were passing
by.
</P>
<P>
At least one Israeli soldier was injured in the blast, the
anonymous security sources added.
</P>
<P>
In Beirut, the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, claimed
responsibility for the attack in a statement, saying that its
fighters detonated the bomb at 8:45 a.m. (0545 GMT) on the road
between Arnoun and Al-Khardali, targeting the Israeli foot patrol.
</P>
<P>
The Shiite Muslim organization, which spearheads a guerrilla
warfare to oust the Israeli occupation forces from the Lebanese
land, stressed that "a certain number of Israeli soldiers were
killed or wounded."
</P>
<P>
In retaliation for the guerrilla operation, Israeli artillery
bombarded the vicinities of Mazraa Hamra and Arnoun in the morning
without causing casualties, according to the security sources.
</P>
<P>
However, the sources noted that today's clash came within the
scope of daily exchanges of fire between Muslim guerrillas and the
Israeli occupation forces on the last active battlefront of the
Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
Nine Israeli soldiers have been killed and more than 40 others
wounded by Hezbollah guerrillas in south Lebanon since the
beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish state established the 1,100-square-kilometer
"security zone" in 1985 to protect northern Israel
from cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, during a tour of the occupation zone
Tuesday, Israel defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai reiterated his
government's claim that Iran is sending weapons to Hezbollah via
Syria, and vowed to continue its fight against the Iranian-backed
guerrillas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
