<HEADLINE> Africa Told to Reduce Military Budgets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 21 (Xinhua) -- African countries should seriously
consider reducing military budgets as a first step towards
averting conflicts, a Zambian parliamentarian said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing over 150 delegates attending the 28th Commonwealth
Parliamentary Association (CPA) Africa region conference,
Frederick Hapunda said cutting down on military expenditure
would help reduce the incidence of conflicts on the continent.
</P>
<P>
"This should be the first step so that more resources are
allocated to the economic development of each nation," said
Hapunda.
</P>
<P>
Hapunda said conflict resolution in Africa could be championed
by regional groupings before involving the Organisation of Africa
Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
The southern African development community last year launched
an organ on politics, defence and security under the chairmanship
of Zimbabwean president Robert Mugabe to monitor and maintain
stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Then regional organisations in Africa should try to resolve
conflicts within their localities through mediation, conciliation
or artitration, not by armed intervention," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
