<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary Supports State Ban on Stock Speculation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A short commentary issued here
today supports a central government regulation that bans
state-owned enterprises and listed companies from stock
speculation.
</P>
<P>
The regulation was jointly issued by the State Council's
Securities Committee, the People's Bank of China, and the State
Economic and Trade Commission recently.
</P>
<P>
The commentary, titled "A good method to promote the
standardized development of the stock market," described the
regulation as an "appropriate prescription for promoting sound
growth of the state-owned enterprises and curbing over-speculation
on the stock market."
</P>
<P>
The commentary noted that it is international common practice
to restrict short-term speculation and encourage long-term
investment in the stock market, which is precisely the aim of the
regulation.
</P>
<P>
The regulation stipulates explicitly that no state-owned
enterprise or listed company is allowed to purchase or sell stocks
within a fixed period of time.
</P>
<P>
The commentary urged the people to follow the instructions of
the Party Central Committee and the State Council, adhere to the
state principle of "law-abiding, supervision, self-discipline, and
standardization" for the stock market operation, and enhance their
awareness of potential risks.
</P>
<P>
"Timely and effective measures should also be taken to prevent
and dissolve risks and to maintain a normal market order and
social stability, thus ensuring a sustained, rapid and sound
development for the national economy," it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary Supports State Ban on Stock Speculation (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The commentary went on to say that the involvement of
state-owned enterprises and listed companies in stock speculation
has not only increased risks for their management, but also
reinforced over-speculation on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
"Those state enterprises and listed companies engaged in stock
speculation are simply not taking care of their own business," it
commented.
</P>
<P>
It conceded that China's stock market, which has been set up
for only six years, still lacks proper legal management and strict
supervision.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, it is particularly necessary for the central
authorities to provide correct guidance for the development of the
market," it noted.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that the recent revival of over-speculation in
China's stock market could be partly attributed to the speculative
activities of a number of state-owned enterprises and listed
companies, which used bank loans or money raised from issue of
shares to buy stocks.
</P>
<P>
"This kind of phenomenon, if tolerated, will not only affect
normal production and management and cause the loss of state
assets, but also disrupt the order of the financial and securities
markets and hurt investors' interests," the commentary said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
