<HEADLINE> Sweden Opposed to EU Border Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Sweden would not accept any
European Union (EU) decision on creating a border-free Europe
should it hurt the interests of non-EU nordic countries, Swedish
Prime Minister Goran Persson said today.
</P>
<P>
Meeting visiting Icelandic Prime Minister David Oddsson here,
Persson said that with Sweden's opposition, the EU could not take
any step which would threaten Iceland and Norway, which are
outside the EU.
</P>
<P>
The EU expects to launch the Schengen Treaty in 1999, which
aims to lift border controls among the 15 EU members and set up
computer databases to help police cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Last December, the five Nordic nations joined the Schengen
countries, which had already embraced 10 Western European
countries. The agreement could not take effect without
ratification by all the EU members' parliaments.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers agreed that Nordic cooperation should
be maintained, even though Sweden, Finland and Denmark had joined
the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
