<HEADLINE> French PM Calls Chirac's China Visit "Extremely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Alain Juppe
today called the results of the state visit paid by President
Jacques Chirac to China last week "extremely positive."
</P>
<P>
In a brief press declaration after a meeting of the French
government chaired by Chirac, Juppe said that the visit was a
"demonstration" that "a strategy of dialogue in the field of human
rights was more effective with the Chinese than a strategy of
confrontation."
</P>
<P>
"On the economic plane, we have been able to mark important
points in a field in which competition is very strong. I am
referring to air transport, with the order of 30 Airbus and 10 ATR
planes (by China)," said Juppe.
</P>
<P>
He called on the government ministers to send a "message of
confidence" to the French voters who will cast their votes in the
legislative elections on May 25 and June 1.
</P>
<P>
"The president stressed that the spirit of enterprise, and the
spirit of conquest have come. He encouraged us... to carry a
message of confidence and growth," said the prime minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
