<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos today urged all political parties in Albania to make every
effort towards a successful holding of the planned June 29
elections.
</P>
<P>
Pangalos said in a statement today that Athens promised to
continue offering the neighboring country every possible assistance
on the diplomatic, economic and humanitarian front.
</P>
<P>
However, he warned against allowing "partisan concerns to
thwart" what he called the historic opportunity offered by the
elections.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the international community would have to
review its position with regard to Albania "if the elections
foundered."
</P>
<P>
"If the elections were not held under free and fair conditions,
the end of Albania's troubles would not be at hand," he said.
</P>
<P>
Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos also warned Tuesday
that the failure by Albanian political parties to reach a compromise
for the elections next month would put into doubt the presence of
the Italian-led multinational force guarding aid supplies.
</P>
<P>
Greek Defense Ministry officials said that Greek troops, now
stationed in Tirana and Vlore, may also be sent to the southern town
of Gjirokaster and to abandoned customs offices on the border with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
Political parties in Albania failed to reach agreement on the
electoral law passed by the parliament last week because it was
approved without the consent of the opposition parties, who
threatened to boycott the elections. 
</P>
