<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Shara's Visit to Moscow Assumes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk
Al-Shara flew to Moscow yesterday. His visit to the former friend
is of special importance in view of the stalled Middle East peace
process, and of the fact that Russia was one of the co-sponsors of
this process.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian diplomatic move came as Damascus tried its best to
search for alternatives to the American role in the peace process,
which has reached an impasse because of the U.S. failure to stay
firm and pressure the Netanyahu government to fulfill its
obligations.
</P>
<P>
It would not be easy to salvage the peace process without a
balanced international stance to pressure Israel to abide by
international resolutions and the Madrid conference principles.
</P>
<P>
Syria is actually seeking to enliven European and Russian roles
to bring about a balanced and effective position in face of the
U.S. stance, which has been considered to be totally aligned to
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Russian attitude towards the peace process, however,
corresponds with that of the European and Arab states with regard
to the demand for implementing the U.N. resolutions and the
land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources in the Syrian capital indicate that Shara
will discuss with his Russian counterpart and other senior
officials ways and means of reactivating the Russian role in the
peace process. They will also exchange views on the current
developments in northern Iraq and examine the influences of the
Turkish-Israeli alliance on the regional countries and even on
central Asian countries. Particularly because Turkey is a NATO
member, diplomats said, the alliance will be a future threat to
Russian security.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian foreign minister will also touch upon improving
Syrian-Russian economic, trade and military relations, which have
suffered setbacks over the past years. Shara's visit assumes
greater importance especially as it will be followed by Russian
military and economic delegations to Syria to mend bilateral
relations and settle outstanding issues between the two countries,
foremost among which is Syria's 10-million-dollar debt. The major
part of it is the payment for the arms delivered to Syria during
the era of the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
Both Syria and Russia have the desire to improve their
political, economic and military relations and Russia is seeking
to come back to the Middle East region. Political observers here
believe Shara's visit to Russia will undoubtedly bring about
rapprochement between the two countries, particularly in the
military field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
