<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC Pledges to Bolster Egypt's Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Leading experts of the International
Finance Corporation (IFC) today pledged to give a hard push to the
private sector of Egypt, which is becoming an investment magnet in
the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
A delegation from the World Bank-affiliated IFC, on a week-long
visit here since May 15, discussed with government and industry
leaders on its activities in Egypt, where privatization and
investment have become a hallmark of a 15-year economic reform
drive.
</P>
<P>
Jannik Lindbaek, IFC executive vice president, hailed the
reform as building "good bases for expansion of the private sector
and attracting both portfolio and direct investment."
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here today, he said that the Corporation
has expanded its activities in Egypt in response to a more
favorable environment within the country for private sector
development.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 20 years, the Corporation has approved 50
projects in Egypt totaling 750 million dollars in the sectors
ranging from tourism, steel and petrochemicals to oil and gas,
leasing and banking.
</P>
<P>
In the next few years, 150-200 million dollars will be invested
a year by IFC, the largest multilateral source of equity and loan
financing for private sector projects in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Calling Egypt one of its most active investment markets in the
Mideast, Lindbaek said IFC's strategy in Egypt is "to promote and
support this private sector development through investment in the
financial sector, infrastructure, tourism and manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
The lastest effort came on Monday when IFC sets up a risk
management facility with National Bank of Egypt (NBE) to allow NBE
to offer private sector clients medium and long-term fixed rate
loan and a variety of risk management products.
</P>
<P>
In fact, a favorable investment climate has already given Egypt
more recognition, said Lindbaek, citing an investment grade
granted to Egyptian paper this year by a leading rating agency and
the inclusion of Egypt in IFC's Investable Stock Market Indices.
</P>
<P>
"IFC's decision is an acknowledgment of tremendous changes in
the Egyptian economy," said Lindbaek, adding that the indices
bring information about the promising Egyptian market to a wide
group of investors and will help encourage more foreign investment
in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
Participation of the private sector represented 60 percent of
the volume of economic activities in Egypt by 1995, a 50 percent
rise over the 1970s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
