<HEADLINE> Hariri Vows to Continue Reconstruction Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik al-Hariri
reaffirmed here today his government's determination to continue
reconstruction despite current stalemate in the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the Third Conference of the
Arab Capital Markets in Beirut, Hariri said "we should continue our
programs of development and continue to attract foreign capital and
investments and open the country to the world markets."
</P>
<P>
Talking about possible effects of the deadlock in the
Middle East peace process on investments in Lebanon and Arab
countries, the prime minister stressed that Lebanon believes in
peace but has never bet on peace.
</P>
<P>
"Lebanon believes in peace," he said, "we are the people
which have suffered much from the war and from outcomes of the war
in various fields of our life."
</P>
<P>
"But we have never bet on peace because betting on peace
means one puts his political and national decision in the hands of
another party which could agree to peace or could not do that,"
the billionaire-turned prime minister noted.
</P>
<P>
Hariri, who is considered by many Lebanese as the architect of
the country's ambitious post-civil war reconstruction and
development, said that his government will continue its schemes of
reconstructing the country and rebuild its infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
"We have not put our national and political decision in the
hands of Israel to let it move them as it wants," the Lebanese
leader underlined.
</P>
<P>
Trying to minimizing the negative impacts resulting from a
possible collapse of the peace process, the prime minister said
that there is not such a big difference between an attainment of
peace and a failure to achieve it as imagined by some people.
</P>
<P>
"There will be various challenges and problems before us if
peace is realized, just as we are facing the current challenges
and problems because peace has not be obtained due to Israel's
intransigence," Hariri added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
