<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's Plan to Pay Off UN Dues Stalls in Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government's
proposal to pay 1 billion U.S. dollars in dues owed to the United
Nations has run aground in the Republican-controlled Congress, the
New York Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The conservative Republicans have been insisting that the
United States would not pay some of the debt if the world body
failed to enact changes required by them.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has held a series of negotiations
with the Republicans in the House and Senate to try to work out an
agreement on the U.N. reforms and due payment.
</P>
<P>
Proposals circulating in the U.S. Congress require everything
from permanently reducing U.S. annual dues to slashing the expense
accounts of the ranking officials, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposals, which have the backing of the Republican
leadership in both houses, the United Nations would also have to
reimburse the cost of American military equipment and support for
U.N. peacekeeping operations, to impose still more budget
restraints and even to allow the General Accounting Office of the
U.S. Congress to check the U.N.'s book.
</P>
<P>
But the administration, in quiet negotiations with the U.S.
Congress, has opposed many of the proposals.
</P>
<P>
The wrangling between the administration and the Republicans
comes only months after new U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
visited Washington in January. During the visit, the U.N. chief
promised to make necessary reforms while both the administration
and Congress pledged that the United States would finally pay off
the owed dues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
