<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Japan is to provide about 61 million U.S. dollars in
soft loan for the Jordan Human Resources Development Sector
Investment Project, Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Planning Rima Khalaf Tuesday signed the
agreement with Japanese Ambassador to Jordan Takayuki Kimura.
</P>
<P>
This soft loan, which is provided by Japan's Overseas Economic
Cooperation Fund, bears an interest rate of 2.7 percent. The
repayment period is 30 years, including a 10-year grace period.
</P>
<P>
Japan has been the second largest aid contributor to Jordan
after the United States since the 1990 Gulf crisis.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Ministry of Energy and Mineral Resources has
submitted the cabinet a report covering international bids to
establish a new oil refinery in Jordan's Red Sea port city Aqaba,
Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The oil refinery is expected to cost 2.2 billion U.S. dollars,
according to Minister of Energy and Mineral Resources Mohammad
Saleh Horani.
</P>
<P>
Horani said the first consortium grouped three U.S. companies
and the other Jordanian and Japanese firms.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will soon examine the bids with other ministries
concerned and with the help of experts from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Amman -- Jordan now suffers large trade deficit, which is
corresponding to approximately one-third of the gross national
product, Prime Minister Abdul Salam Majali said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian business community and industries should intensify
their efforts and improve product quality so as to boost export
and offset the deficit, said Majali while addressing the opening
session of the 23rd meeting of the Federation of Jordanian
Chambers of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Ukraine are pondering on the establishment
of a joint bank, a Cairo-based Ukrainian trade center and a trade
data center.
</P>
<P>
According to today's Cairo Press Review, Egypt's Minister of
Economy and International Cooperation Nawal al Tatawi Tuesday
agreed with a visiting Ukrainian businessmen and bankers delegation
on raising the idea of the joint bank and the centers for
discussion during the upcoming session of the Egyptian-Ukrainian
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The idea was forwarded by Ukraine, which believes that the bank
would be the best medium to facilitate trade exchanges between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian delegation maintained that the information center
will be useful for businessmen wishing to import Egyptian products
such as ceramics and construction material and for those hoping
to contribute to oil and natural gas prospecting operations in
Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
