<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> War Lingers in Newly-Born Democratic Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Guo Ming)
</P>
<P>
KINSHASA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Intensive fighting continued
today in Zaire's western Lower Zaire Province between troops of
Laurent Kabila, Head of State of the newly-born Democratic
Republic of Congo, and soldiers loyal to exiled former President
Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
"Kabila's advancing troops met fierce resistence from the
Mobutu loyalists in Matadi," said a military observer, referring
to the country's only seaport 400 km west of Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, as Kabila arrived at Kinshasa, his people's
liberation army blocked the no. 1 high way, the only road on
Lower Zaire's narrow strip of land connecting the country's vast
land to the Atlantic ocean, military sources said, adding the
move was aimed at ensuring security of the capital.
</P>
<P>
"There is no way we could sit back and relax because the
country is still at war," said a military spokesman of Kabila,
who is also chairman of the ruling Alliance of Democratic Forces
for the Liberation of Congo-Zaire (ADFL).
</P>
<P>
"And the newly-born Democratic of Congo is facing many other
difficulties," he added.
</P>
<P>
Foreign diplomats here said Kabila's top priority is to seek
an immediate end to the armed conflicts still lingering in the
country after he toppled the Mobutu administration and announcing
himself to be Head of State of the Democratic Republic of Congo
on May 17.
</P>
<P>
"How to liberate the contry's last zone still controlled by
Mobutu loyalists, is above all the concerns of President Kabila,"
said one of his aides.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, after presiding over an urgent military meeting of the
ADFL in Kinshasa today, ordered reinforcement to the Matadi
fronts.
</P>
<P>
The narrow strip of land is very important to the newly-born
Democratic Republic of Congo, where Matadi seaport, a major sea
passage is located.
</P>
<P>
So far Kabila has not yet made any formal announcement on the
formation of his new government. Kabila may swear in his new
government anytime from now, which will "mark a new chapter in
the history of Congo (Zaire)," said one of Kabila's aides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Criticizes Glamorization of Heroin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today called on the country's fashion industry to stop glamorizing
heroin use.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gathering of U.S. mayors, Clinton said that some
industry leaders have already admitted the so-called practice of
heroin chic.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "They're admitting flat-out that images projected
in fashion photos in the last few years has made heroin addiction
seem glamorous and sexy and cool."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "You do not need to glamorize addiction to sell
clothes.... The glorification of heroin is not creative, it's
destructive."
</P>
<P>
He said that heroin is increasingly becoming the drug of choice
on college campuses and elsewhere, in part because of the pictures
that young people see.
</P>
<P>
But he also said new statistics showing a drop in the use of
methamphetamine in key Western cities, eight of 10 which he said
showed drops of between 7 percent and 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and his top anti-drug lieutenants met with about 80
members of the U.S. Conference of Mayors at the White House for a
national forum on drugs.
</P>
<P>
The president said drug use remains "a problem of every
American citizen," and he called on everyone to stick to tough,
intolerant attitudes against drugs even if "there might be a
little money to be made out of it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
