<HEADLINE> French Bank to Invest more in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of the
French Development Bank (CFD), Antoine Peuillieute, said today
that his bank will increase investments in agricultural, energy
and water supply sectors in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference at the end of his two-day visit
to Tanzania, Peuillieute said that through its subsidiary, the
CFD has in the last three years invested 10 million US Dollars in
loans and equity in seven projects in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said the investment was involved in finance, horticulture,
agro-food processing, brewing and leather industries, listing
some of the firms that have secured loans and equity as the
Tanzania Breweries Limited, Eurafrican Bank and Moshi Tanneries.
</P>
<P>
Peuillieute said CFD has so far committed 53 million US
Dollars for loans and equity for various projects in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said the move was in line with the French government's
decision to increase investments and economic involvement in the
so-called non-francophone countries in Africa, latin America and
East Asia.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Peuillieute met President Benjamin
Mkapa, Fiance Minister Daniel Yona and Centerl Bank Governor
Idris Rashidi.
</P>
<P>
CFD was established in 1941. At present it is a key component
of French official development assistance through grants and
concessional loans to developing countries. In January, this
year, CFD set up a regional office in Nairobi, Kenya, which is
responsible for activities in Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Rwanda and
Brundi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
