<HEADLINE> Egypt Renews Call for Stopping Settlement Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Egypt today renewed its call for
stopping the Jewish settlement construction on Arab land, an issue
that has taken the center stage in the two-month-old Mideast peace
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak made the appeal during talks
with Palestinian President Yasser Arafat who arrived here today as
the deadlocked peace process shows no sign of a breakthrough,
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said that Arafat expounded to Mubarak the latest
developments in the occupied lands and his view of the way to
circumvent the crisis. The discussions might continue tonight and
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said the Palestinians stand firm in their demand for
halting Israeli settlement in order to restart the talks which
came to a standstill after Israel started construction of a new
neighborhood in Arab East Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
Israel refused to budge on its settlement building in Jerusalem
which it wants to have as future capital while the Palestinians
insisted on stopping the project before resuming the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Mubarak's proposal to halt the project for six
months, Moussa said what the president meant is that settlements
should be stopped completely in order to "pave the way for
restarting serious and significant negotiations."
</P>
<P>
"Bulldozers' work can never create an appropriate atmosphere
for serious and successful negotiations," he added.
</P>
<P>
The top Egyptian diplomat also played down the significance of
an American report saying that one quarter of the existing Jewish
settlement is empty.
</P>
<P>
"The American stance against Israeli settlement policy is
known. But there should be a way to revive the peace process
which can not be maintained with the continuation of settlements
especially in Jerusalem," he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia as a co-sponsors of the peace process should take part
in the pooled efforts to salvage peace, he said, however, the
U.S. role is still important.
</P>
<P>
Contacts are still going on with the U.S. besides the Europeans
whose role "is welcomed," he said, adding that Mubarak has urged a
"projected European role" in the peace process during his recent
visit to Germany.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been deeply involved in the Mideast peace process
since it signed a peace deal with Israel in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Secret crisis talks overnight Tuesday between Israel and the
Palestinians failed to ease a two-month-old deadlock.
</P>
<P>
After U.S. Mideast coordinator Dennis Ross left the region
empty-handed last weekend, Arafat blamed the lack of American
pressure on Israel for a breakdown of the "core bargain" of the
1993 Israeli-PLO Oslo deal.
</P>
<P>
Disappointed with Ross' performance during the nine-day
mission, he has asked U.S. President Bill Clinton to personally
get involved in efforts to break the impasse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
