<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Genomics Company Discovers Asthma Gene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 21 (Xinhua) -- An American genomics company
announced today that it has discovered a gene responsible for
asthma.
</P>
<P>
Sequana Therapeutics, Inc., based in La Jolla, southern
California, said that the discovery will provide new clues into
improved diagnosis and treatment of asthma, the leading cause of
hospitalization and absenteeism in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Asthma affects approximately 100 million people worldwide and
costs the United States more than 6 billion dollars in diagnosis,
treatment and lost wages. About 15 million people, including
nearly 5 million children, suffer from asthma in the U.S., and
prevalence of the disease has doubled over the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
Rate of asthma emergency room visits and death in urban areas
are several times the national average, according to Sequana
experts. There is no known cure fo this epidemic, and current
treatments are limited to reducing inflammation or controlling
airway construction.
</P>
<P>
"Sequana's gene discovery is perhaps this country's most
important finding in the etiology of asthma," said Richard D.
O'Connor, clinical professor of pediatrics at the University of
California, San Diego, School of Medicine. "This landmark
discovery will bring us one step closer to finding better drugs to
address this growing epidemic."
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1993 and staffed with 200 researchers, Sequana is a
leading genomics company that uses industrial scale gene finding
technologies and functional genomics to develop products aimed at
diagnosing and treating common human diseases. Its gene discovery
programs cover asthma, diabetes, obesity, osteoporosis,
schizophrenia and manic depression. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
