<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Advises Zaire's New Leader to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Y. Museveni
today advised Zaire's new leader Laurent Kabila to maintain
unity and form a broad-based national government in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference held here this evening,
Museveni noted that there are many groups against former Zairean
leader Mobutu Sese Seko which are not necessarily working with
Kabila. Therefore, he said, the first step for Kabila to take is
to maintain unity by involving all the political groups in a
bid to form a broad-based government.
</P>
<P>
But Kabila cannot lose his control and his own supporters must
have majority within that government, so that they can do things
through their programs, Museveni said.
</P>
<P>
The second step is to open up infrastructure including roads
and rivers, he suggested.
</P>
<P>
Macro economic stabilization is the third step, because
inflation in Zaire is very high, he added.
</P>
<P>
On situation in northern Uganda, Museveni said that peace is
prevailing in the part of the country, though there are now small
groups of rebels making insurgency.
</P>
<P>
"We are now getting them one by one. They are surrendering to
us by a very big number, so the situation in the that part of the
country is tremendously good," he said.
</P>
<P>
The rebel Lord's Resistance Army which has its bases in
southern Sudan has since 1987 been acting in northern Uganda,
disstabilizing the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
