<HEADLINE> ECOMOG to Recover Arms After Liberia's Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping force
in Liberia, known as ECOMOG, said today it will extend its
current operation to recover hidden arms in that country even
after the elections later this year.
</P>
<P>
Liberia's legislative and presidential elections, originally
scheduled for May 30, have been shifted to July.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the sub-region were at a meeting today in Abuja,
capital of Nigeria, to decide a new date. But the outcome of the
meeting is yet to be known.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement by press secretary to ECOMOG
Commander Victor Malu, the force is determined to considerably
reduce the level of illegal arms before its departure.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG succeeded in disarming Liberia's former factional
fighters and demobilizing the factions four months ago. A lot of
arms hidden by the various factions have since been discovered.
</P>
<P>
The campaign to recover hidden weapons is designed to rid
Liberia of illegal arms and improve the security situation in the
country.
</P>
<P>
According to Malu, ECOMOG is willing to contribute to the
transparency of the rescheduled elections so as to create the
public support needed to deal with those who might want to resist
the result of the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
