<HEADLINE> France Demands Probing Death of Nationals in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Guo Ming)
</P>
<P>
KINSHASA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The French government today
demanded that the authorities of the newly-born Democratic Republic
of Congo to probe the killing of two French nationals in
Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
The message was delivered by French ambassador to Zaire,
Jacques Rummelhardt, who made contact this afternoon with the
authorities of Democratic Congo in capital Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Two French businessmen were killed on Tuesday night by
armed looters believed to be members of the exiled Zairean
president Mobutu Sese Seko's army, which had already been
defeated by Kabila's People's Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
These scattered soldiers of Mobutu's army fled with their arms
as Kabila's troops "liberated" Kinshasa on May 17 to finally
topple the Mobutu regime. Kinshasa is the last major city
captured by Kabila's soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the French ambassador also handed over an official
four-point message to Kabila's Alliance of Democratic Forces for
the Liberation of Congo-Zaire (ADFL), which currently serves as
the ruling authorities of the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
Although content of the message was not made public,
observers said France, the major western power to support the
falling regime of Mobutu, might just as well modify its stance and
slowly move into the process of recognizing Kabila's Democratic
Republic of Congo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
