<HEADLINE> Swazi Govt Denies Closing Independent Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Swazi government has
denied claims that it intended to close down the kingdom's only
independent newspaper, "The Times of Swaziland".
</P>
<P>
The denial came in the wake of calls from a number of senate
members last week for the government to close the publication
after it published an article claiming King Mswati III had failed
to pay rates on a property he owned, according to South African press
reports.
</P>
<P>
However, the government has apparently ordered most government
departments and parastatals not to advertise in the newspaper, of
which about half of the newspaper's advertising revenue came from
such advertising.
</P>
<P>
The paper's news editor, Vusi Ginindza, confirmed the verbal
order on Monday and said the publication had already had
cancellations from some departments.
</P>
<P>
Ginindza said the order to government departments and
parastatals was apparently in retaliation for the article.
</P>
<P>
The Times of Swaziland has a daily circulation of about 11,000
at present. 
</P>
