<HEADLINE> S.Africa Starts Destroying Anti-Personnel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- South Africa today started
destroying its stockpile of 261,423 anti-personnel landmines by
blowing up 4,700 of the devices in a controlled explosion in
Northern Cape Province.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Joe Modise pressed the button which sparked
the blast at Alkantpan Military Base near Copperton in the
province, proclaiming the event a "historic" moment, reported the
South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
Modise told reporters that the event, witnessed by numerous
foreign dignitaries and South African officials, signified the
country's commitment to eradicating what he described as a very
cruel weapon.
</P>
<P>
He further pointed out that South Africa would never again
produce anti-personnel landmines for war purposes, hoping the
rest of the world would follow suit.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, which in February became the first African
country to place an outright ban on these devices, would destroy
the bulk of its stockpile systematically at Alkantpan over the
next five months, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
