<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President: Greek Cypriot Side Ready for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Greek Cypriot side will accept
an invitation to hold direct talks with the Turkish Cypriot side
even though the latter has given no evidence of a shift from its
intransigent position, Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides said
here today.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at the opening of the 22nd International
State Fair, which was attended by about 2,000 local and foreign
exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
"We have indicated to U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan that
the Turkish side has given no sign of any intention to shift
from its well-known positions on the basic aspects of the
Cyprus problem and that he would, therefore, have to consider
seriously the consequences of a new failure," the President
said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "our side will not refuse to attend" direct
talks, if Annan decides to call the talks. "We shall attend, once
more, with goodwill as we are keen to reach a settlement the
soonest possible," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the content of the talks, Clerides said that "we
shall insist that the talks should concentrate on discussion of
the basic aspects of the Cyprus problem" -- matters relating to
sovereignty, security, territorial adjustments, the constitution
and guarantees of a future federal state of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been conducting proximity talks with the Greek
and Turkish sides in Cyprus since March, aimed at preparing
the ground for direct negotiations between Clerides and Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Chief Annan said earlier this week that he hopes to
have the leaders of the two communities in Cyprus for
face-to-face discussion in New York next month.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
