<HEADLINE> 8,000 Hectares of Forests Razed in North-eastern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Rammpant fire incidences in
Tanga region, north-eastern Tanzania this year razed about 8,675
hectares of natural forests, mainly forest reserves.
</P>
<P>
Felician Kilahama, farm forestry advisor with the Tanga-based
East Usambara Catchment Forest Project, made the statements in an
interview with the Tanzania News Agency (SHIHATA) here today.
</P>
<P>
"With a crude value of 10,000 Tanzania Shillings, about 16.6
US Dollars, per hectare, it means some 86.75 million T.Shs, about
144,580 Dollars, in value," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the causes of the fire, Kilahama said whether wet
or dry, fire does not happen naturally in forests or
miraculously. He noted that it was directly started by people in
one way or another.
</P>
<P>
Tanga, like the rest regions of Tanzania, faced an
extra-ordinary dry period this year compared to previous years.
</P>
<P>
The expert emphasized the need for villagers and local
governments to make efforts to prevent and control outbreaks of
fire in forest areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
