<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Caribbean Economies Post Growth in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TORONTO, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Most of the 17 borrowing member
economies of the Caribbean Development Bank (CDB) registered
economic growth, CDB President Neville Nicholls said here today.
</P>
<P>
A few of these economies posted "significant growth", the
president noted while presenting the bank's annual report to its
27th annual Board of Governors meeting, which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
"Guyana sustained the process of economic recovery of the past
few years with a growth rate of almost eight percent in 1996,"
Nicholls said.
</P>
<P>
The Cayman Islands continued to be vibrant with five percent
growth, and Barbados recorded "a very encouraging" growth of 4.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Most of the other economies experienced growth ranging from
slightly above three percent to just under one percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the economies of Auguilla and Montserrat did not
fared quite as well, mainly because of the "highly damaging
effects of an erupting volcano."
</P>
<P>
Overall, the economic performance in the region depended
heavily on factors in the international economy where growth in
1996 dipped below the levels achieved during the previous two
years, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, the performance of the tourism sector, which has a
pervasive influence on most Caribbean economies, was dampened
mainly by competition from high public-interest activities in the
United States of America and fear of dangerous weather systems in
the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
In other major sectors, the Caribbean region continued to face
the difficulties of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The banana industry battled harsh weather, low fruit quality
and uncertain market prospects in Europe.
</P>
<P>
"And whereas the production of raw sugar expanded, considerable
threat to its trading preferences exist within the new
dispensations of the World Trade Organization," he noted.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, economic and institutional adjustment in the region
continued to be "a critical area for policy action" so as to gain
"competitiveness within the framework of market liberalization,"
he noted.
</P>
<P>
To help its borrowing member economies, the bank provided the
region with a total of 104.8 million U.S. dollars of new loans in
1996.
</P>
<P>
CDB is a subregional financial institution designed to foster
economic growth and development in the region while promoting
regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
It is currently composed of 17 regional borrowing members,
three regional non-borrowing members and five non-regional
members.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1969, the bank has been headquartered in Bridgetown,
Barbados. 
</P>
</TEXT>
