<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Sees High Maternal Mortality Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria accounts for 15 percent of
the annual global maternal mortality, with 800 out of 100,000
mothers died annually during child birth, an expert said today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, one in every 13 Nigerian women died from pregnancy
complications, in contrast to one in 69 in southeast Asia and one
in 3,200 in western Europe.
</P>
<P>
Major factors of the deaths include maemorrhage, obstructed
labor and unsafe abortion, said Adenike Grange, a World Health
Organization (WHO) adviser in maternal and child
health/reproductive health.
</P>
<P>
About 20 percent of the conditions were aggravated by
pre-existing anaemia and malaria, she added.
</P>
<P>
The WHO expert said that maternal mortality occurred more
among teenage mothers, whose conditions arose mainly from
physiological immaturity and behavioral factors.
</P>
<P>
Between 38 and 68 percent teenage mothers sought care for
post-abortion complications, she said, adding that their children
were at higher risks of dying than those born to older mothers.
</P>
<P>
According to the expert, one in every five Nigerian children
between the ages of two and five were at the risk of dying from
low birth weight, hypothermia and birth asphyxia.
</P>
<P>
"These are reflections of poor maternal care and preventable
diseases like malaria, diarroea and measles," she said, quoted by
the News Agency of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
She also said that adolescent mothers were more vulnerable to
sexually-transmitted diseases such as AIDS.
</P>
<P>
According to the WHO expert, Nigeria needs reproductive health
programs that will make information available to all member of
the family and "enable women to go safely through pregnancy and
provide couples with the best chance of having healthy infants".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
