<HEADLINE> Nigeria Records High Child Mortality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has recorded a high child
mortality rate of 91 per 1,000 live births, according to Health
Minister Ihechukwu Madubuike.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a 1993 statistics, the minister noted that more than 80
percent of such cases were caused by childhood diseases, the News
Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
At a workshop on Integratd Management of Childhood Illness on
Tuesday in Abuja, capital of Nigeria, the minister said that 191
per 1,100 children under the age of five die from comon preventable
childhood diseases such as malaria, measles, diarrhoea, malnutrition
and acute respiratory infection.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the government has decided to use the integrated
approach which, he said, "would allow health workers to see a patient
in totality in view of observed overlaps in clinical presentations of
some of the childhood diseases."  
</P>
