<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Central Bank's Supervisory Role Curbed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Eddie George, Governor of Bank of
England, said today that he was surprised at the timing of the
announcement by Chancellor Gordon Brown that the Bank's
supervisory role is to be taken away.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, George said that while he
had no difficulty with the direction in which supervision is
moving, "implementation is going to be difficult".
</P>
<P>
Britain is not the first country to move responsibility for
banking supervision away from its central bank. The general trend
now in the world appears to be towards a separation between
central banks and financial supervision.
</P>
<P>
Chancellor Brown said at a dinner party last night that the
current regulatory structure was "inefficient, confusing for
investors and lacks accountability and a clear allocation of
responsibilities".
</P>
<P>
The powers of the Securities and Investments Board will be
strengthened to bring together regulation of banking, securities
and insurance.
</P>
<P>
"This will improve the competitiveness of the sector and create
a regulatory regime to meet the challenges of the 21st century,"
the Chancellor added.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he is going to resign after his bank was stripped
of the power of supervision, the Governor said he did not
"seriously consider resigning" as a result.
</P>
<P>
George said it is "enormously important" that the newly
strengthened Securities and Investments Board does not
over-regulate.
</P>
<P>
However, the Governor said that given the fact that the world
may reach a stage where it is difficult to distinguish a bank from
another financial institution, it makes "entirely good sense to
move to a world that we are not in now".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
