<HEADLINE> Bildt Urges Bosnians to Adopt Economic Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- A senior international official
today warned the Bosnian parties of the possibility of reducing
financial assistance if they do not adopt required economic laws
before a ministerial meeting on Bosnia later this month.
</P>
<P>
Carl Bildt, High Representative in charge of the Dayton peace
accords implementation, said in a statement that the Bosnian
council of ministers and presidency should agree on the package of
legislation before the conference on May 30, in Sintra, Portugal,
of foreign ministers of the Steering Board of the Peace
Implementation Council.
</P>
<P>
"I see no reason why this should not be done in time for
Sintra," Bildt said. "If this does not occur, some members of the
international community might start to reconsider the level of the
assistance they are willing to pledge."
</P>
<P>
Bildt has insisted on passing the economic laws as the
precondition for holding an international donors' conference for
Bosnia and due to the failure for the Bosnian parties to do so,
the conference has been repeatedly postponed.
</P>
<P>
Bildt also said in the statement that the Sintra meeting will
set out the international community's strategy for Bosnia in the
following months and appoint his successor.
</P>
<P>
"A Sintra Declaration will be adopted at the meeting,
expressing the determination of the international community to
press forward with implementation of the Peace Agreement, and
calling on the authorities of Bosnia and Herzegovina to fully live
up to their responsibilities," Bildt said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
