<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Caspian Sea Countries Meet on Division of Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Russia, Kazakhstan, Azerbaijan,
Turkmenistan and Iran today opened a special meeting on dividing
the natural resources of the Caspian Sea and the its future
status.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Kazakhstan Foreign Minister
Kasymzhomart Tokayev said the central task of the meeting is to
seek a solution to the legal status of the Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
The settlement of its status would be conducive to the
exploitation of natural resources in the Caspian, and the
protection of its environment, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Caspian Sea, which is the largest inland body of water in
the world, abounds in oil and natural gas. Its division is of
strategic importance to the countries around it.
</P>
<P>
So far, there have been four draft treaties on the status of
the Caspian Sea by Russia, Kazakhstan, Azerbaijan and Iran. Russia
and Iran agreed to share the right of exploitation in the center
of the sea, while the other two counties wanted to divide it more
completely.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which ends tomorrow, will also discuss shipping,
fisheries and environmental issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Rejects U.S. Attack on Refugee Repatriation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- German Interior Minister Manfred
Kanther today rejected the U.S. criticism on Bonn's plans to
send back Bosnian refugees living in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Bonn needs no advice on how to deal with the issue, Kanther
said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said, "Civil war refugees are guests for a limited
time and this time is ticking away."
</P>
<P>
He said that of about 30,000 Bosnian refugees who had returned
home from Germany so far, only 191 were actually expelled. "There
are no mass deportations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kanther made the remarks in response to a call from U.S. State
Department spokesman, Nicholas Burns, Wednesday asking the German
government to differentiate between Bosnian refugees who wanted to
return home and those who could not return because of repression
from Croatian or Serbian mobs.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian refugees were given political asylum in Germany and
therefore could not apply for work permits and had to be supplied
with public housing.
</P>
<P>
The financial burden to support refugees has led to increasing
public pressure on the German government to begin repatriate some
of them.
</P>
<P>
Germany has taken in about 350,000 Bosnian refugees since war
erupted there in 1992, far more the number accepted by any other
country. Earlier this year, the German government announced that
it would begin sending back refugees since the fighting had
stopped.
</P>
<P>
The United States has accepted 38,000 Bosnian refugees since
1992 and has expressed willingness to take in another 18,000 this
year, including about 5,000 from Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
