<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Forecasts More Ocean Disasters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- China will have natural ocean
disasters with greater frequency and severity this year, with a
large area of the East China Sea as the center, says the National
Bureau of Oceangraphy.
</P>
<P>
Ye Renmiao, director of the NBO Ocean Monitoring Department,
said that three or four tidal storms caused by typhoons are
expected to hit coastal areas of provinces in southern and eastern
China, such as Guangdong, Fujian, Zhejiang, Jiangsu, Hainan, and
Guangxi, between July and October.
</P>
<P>
The number of days with destructive waves, above four meters
high, will be more than last year's 300 days, and more will be
caused by tropical cyclones. Huge waves are quite likely to affect
parts of the Yellow Sea and the East China Sea, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
But, he added, there will be less sea ice in the Bohai Bay and
northern Yellow sea from November 1997 to March 1998 than in
the same period of in the previous corresponding period, he said.
</P>
<P>
There will be an "el nino" phenomenon between November to
December this year, which refers to rapid rises of temperature in
tropical areas of the eastern Pacific, and tends to be followed by
severe floods or droughts the following year in Asia and America,
he added.
</P>
<P>
"NBO has intensified its monitoring efforts by reinforcing its
work staff to put into operation various forecasting methods,
checking its facilities, and strengthening the consultation
system," said Yu Zhouwen, director of the NBO Marine Environmental
Forecasting Center.
</P>
<P>
With rapid economic development of China's coastal areas, the
annual economic losses caused by ocean disasters have also risen
drastically, from about one billion yuan (120 million US dollars)
in early 1980s to some 20 billion yuan (2.4 billion US dollars) in
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
