<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Hardline Policy Damages Palestinian Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 22 (Xinhua) - Israeli government's hardline policy
has damaged the Palestinian economy in the West Bank and the Gaza
Strip since the two sides signed the Oslo peace agreement in
1993, a U.N.-sponsored seminar concluded today.
</P>
<P>
Israel's continuous closure of the Palestinian territories has
led to some 1.2 billion U.S. dollars loss to the Palestinian
economy, this was indicated by U.N. statistics brought to the
three-day seminar entitled "Promoting Palestinian Human Development."
</P>
<P>
The seminar was organized by the U.N. Committee on the Exercise
of the Inalienable Rights of the Palestinian people (CEIRPP) and
attended by more than 25 countries and several U.N. agencies.
</P>
<P>
"An Israeli siege is imposed around Palestinian territories,"
said Palestinian Economic Minister Mahir Masri at the meeting,
"The Palestinian economy is divided into two parts because of the
closure enforced on the west Bank and Gaza Strip, therefore the
Palestinian market is divided as well," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Palestinian-made goods are not able to move from Gaza to the
West Bank and vice versa. And they also find it difficult to reach
Jordanian, Egyptian, other Arab and European markets. Palestinian
individuals are not able to move freely. Therefore all economic
development elements are missing ... This will lead the the
destruction of the peace process and bring disaster to the
region," said Masri.
</P>
<P>
Statistics here indicate that Israel closed the Palestinian
territories for 91 day in 1993, 71 days in 1994, 125 days in 1995
and 310 days in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Nasir Qadwa, Palestinian representative at the U.N., said that
the goal of Israeli closure is to keep the Palestinian
economy "hostage" in order to continue the Jewish state's
monopolization of the Palestinian markets.
</P>
<P>
The closure policy has given rise to unemployment, decrease of
income, and poverty in the west Bank and Gaza, said the
participants at the seminar.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment in Gaza is currently estimated at a depressing
50-60 percent, with the highest jobless rate in the refugee
camps, said Jean-Michel Dumont, secretary-general of the
Brussels-based Parliament Association for Euro-Arab Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In the West Bank, the rate is only 24 percent, but there is a
10-12 percent who are severely under-employed, said the
secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
Many Palestinians lost their income during the closures which
resulted as well in decreasing demand on Palestinian products in
the West Bank and Gaza, said Dumont.
</P>
<P>
Income per capita has dropped from 1,800 dollars a year in the
West Bank and 1,200 dollars a year in Gaza to 950 dollars and 600
dollars respectively, due to the border closures following the
1993 Oslo peace accord, he added.
</P>
<P>
Diab Alloush, deputy minister of social affairs at the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) said that continuous
closures, absence of political stability in the self-rule areas
and the confiscation of the lands by Israel also lead to poverty
increase among the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Based on 1997 figures which set families whose annual income
fall less than 998.5 dollars as below the poverty line, the deputy
minister estimated the present poverty rate at 20 percent in the
West Bank and at 40 percent in the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
If the Israeli poverty standards of 500 dollars per month are
applied, Alloush said, "poverty line in the PNA territories will
jump to 60-70 percent."
</P>
<P>
Despite economic hardships, the PNA is still trying to
eradicate poverty through employing more than 35,000 people during
the closure time and giving annual pension to more than 30,000
families at a monthly cost of 700,000 dollars, he added.
</P>
<P>
The participants called on the U.N. and the U.S. to pressure
Israel to change its hardline policy and end its closure, in order
to solve Palestinians' current problem.
</P>
<P>
Dumont accused the U.S. of being biased and called for a
balanced mediation to solve the deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Abu Libdeh, President of the Palestinian Central Bureau
of Statistics, called on the U.N. to inject funds into the
Palestinian institutions involved in this process to help them
shed poverty and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, under the mediation of the U.S., Israel and the
Palestinians signed the Oslo agreement to put aside decades of
hostility and build peace together. However, Israel has failed to
live up to its promises. The tightening of the closure of the
West Bank and Gaza Strip and the construction of Jewish
settlements in East Jerusalem have helped worsen the situation and
brought the process to a deadlock. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
