<HEADLINE> China Tightens Control over Special Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- China has tightened control over
both the production and sale of a number of special medicines, in
a bid to prevent them from falling into the hands of drug dealers
or addicts.
</P>
<P>
The State Pharmaceutical Administration recently issued a
circular to its subordinates across the country, requiring them to
strengthen the management of various kinds of special medicines,
such as narcotic and psychiatric medicine and ephedrine.
</P>
<P>
The circular noted that at present, some producers and dealers
of the special medicines lack safety awareness and suffer lax
management, while a number of enterprises have been illegally
producing special medicines without state approval.
</P>
<P>
"Due to these factors, the country's drug dealers and addicts
have targeted the links of production and sales for the special
medicines to acquire drugs or raw materials for drugs," it added.
</P>
<P>
It said that the central government would introduce a new
system to conduct necessary examinations on the purchase of
ephedrine, and anyone wants to buy ephedrine must first apply for
an official certificate.
</P>
<P>
"No cash trade is allowed in the dealing of ephedrine, and
domestic sales of this medicine can only be handled by
state-authorized units," it added.
</P>
<P>
It went on to say that four enterprises in northhwest China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region producing ephedrine without state
authorization would be shut down, while governments in major
tea-planting provinces should severely crack down on illegal local
activities of producing natural caffeine.
</P>
<P>
"Later on, any producers or dealers of special medicines, whose
products or goods are missing, stolen or flow into any illegal
channels as a result of poor management, will be deprived of the
rights to produce or sell special medicines," it concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
