<HEADLINE> Syria: Talks with Israel Should be Resumed From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- A prominent Syrian figure said
here today that stalemated negotiations with Israel should be
resumed from the point they were suspended in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
The remark was made by Abdulla Al Ahmar, secretary general of
ruling Arab Socialist Party of Syria, at a meeting here today with
Nayef Hawatmeh, secretary general of the Damascus-based Democratic
Front for the Liberation of the Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Ahmar reiterated Syria's firm stance on the resumption of talks
with Israel, accusing the Netanyahu government of breaching the
peace accord and stalling the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
According to informed sources here, Ahmar reaffirmed Syria's keen
interest in achieving comprehensive peace in conformity with
international resolutions. Peace should be attained on the basis
of Israeli withdrawal to the border lines before June 4, 1967 and
from Arab Jerusalem, and on the recognition of Palestinian
people's right of self determination, the secretary general said.
</P>
<P>
Hawatmeh said during the meeting that settlements and
negotiations cannot go together. He stressed full Palestinian
solidarity with Syria's stance on the resumption of negotiations
from the point they was suspended.
</P>
<P>
Hawatmeh further said the present predicament of the Mideast
peace process necessitates a new move. This move should be in
clear response to the Arab popular movement and facilitate the
formation of a mechanism for dialogues and the convocation of a
conference bracing all factions, parties and national forces
throughout the Arab world, he said.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that Syria would take the initiative of fulfilling
such a qualitative move, in addition to its efforts to strengthen
Arab solidarity and to call for an Arab summit to tackle the current
developments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
