<HEADLINE> Deep Sea Robot to Be Used in Mining (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, May 22 (Xinhua) -- China's first mission for its
deep sea robot, which can dive 6,000 meters under the sea, will be
sea surveys in north-east Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
"The robot will conduct dozens of sea-bed surveys for
polymetallic nodules in the Pioneer Area, granted by the U.N. in
1991 for deep sea-bed mining, marking a turning point in its
development from the experimentation to the utilization stage,"
said Feng Xisheng, chief designer of the project.
</P>
<P>
"The robot can work under the deep sea for eight hours at a
time, and be controlled cablelessly," he added.
</P>
<P>
The project, one of the key projects of China's hi-tech
development "863" program, began in 1992. Based on technological
co-operation with Russia, the robot passed initial testing
conducted in the Pioneer Area in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"The development of the deep sea robot is a comprehensive
project covering several technological fields," said Guo Shiqin,
chief engineer of the China Ocean Resources Research and
Development Association, which organized two investigation cruises
to the Pioneer area for the polymetallic nodules.
</P>
<P>
Guo said the project involved deep diving, sealing, automatic
control, television, and communications technologies, and the
development of the robot is regarded as challenging as the
development of space technologies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
