<HEADLINE> Deep Sea Robot to Be Used in Mining  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More than 97 percent of the ocean is less deep than 6,000
meters, and the successful development of the robot means most of
the earth's ocean floor is no longer inaccessible to the mankind.
</P>
<P>
With such advantages as high efficiency, high adaptability, and
broad-range utilization, the development of the deep sea robot has
been a focus of competition among countries in the world, in which
the United States, Japan, and France are leading the way, and the
successful use of the robot will bring China up to the ranks of
the advanced countries in this field.
</P>
<P>
"China has made steady progress in the development of the
robot," said an official with the high-tech department of the
State Science and Technology Commission, adding that a series of
robots including wall-climbing, automatic navigation, pipe line,
shaft mining, and welding has entered into or nearing the
utilization stage.
</P>
<P>
"The successful development and utilization of the deep sea
robot will mark a technological breakthrough in the field," he
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
The deep sea robot has began its trip from Guangzhou to the
north-east Pacific to carry out the sea-bed surveys for the
polymetallic nodules. The voyage will last more than a half year.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
