<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Fires Defense Minister, Chief of Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today dismissed Defense Minister Igor Rodionov and the chief of
the general staff, General Viktor Samsonov, for "doing a bad job"
in reforming the army, Defense Council Secretary Yuri Baturin said.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the surprising decision at today's meeting of the
Defense Council, Yeltsin also appointed Igor Sergeyev,
Commander-in-Chief of the Strategic Missile Forces, as acting
defense minister.
</P>
<P>
The president rebuked Rodionov, who was appointed last July,
for doing nothing to restructure the armed forces and curb rampant
corruption.
</P>
<P>
"I am not simply dissatisfied, I am indignant over the state of
reforms in the army and the general state of the armed forces,"
Yeltsin said while chairing the meeting to discuss military
reforms.
</P>
<P>
He said Rodionov did "a bad job" in military reorganization,
one of Yeltsin's re-election promises last year. Yeltsin, also the
commander-in-chief of the armed forces, had pledged to overhaul
the present conscription system to build a modern, professional
army by 2000.
</P>
<P>
"The soldier is losing weight while the general is getting
fatter," Yeltsin said. "Many of you will not be here if you
proceed like this."
</P>
<P>
Baturin said Rodionov, under scathing fire from
the president, had refused to deliver a scheduled report at the
meeting, saying the speaking time set by Yeltsin was too
short. Samsonov followed suit.
</P>
<P>
He said Yeltsin signed the dismissal order immediately after
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Senior politicians and military generals have been divided over
the reduction of troops, which Yeltsin expects to ease the
pressure of severe money shortages, and salvage the army beset by
poor training and high-level corruption.
</P>
<P>
Some are reluctant to cut the troops, saying the strength of
the Russian army would be eroded by hasty reductions. Rodionov had
insisted the reform began only after the state increased military
spending.
</P>
<P>
But Yeltsin said Russia, under economic strains, should start
reforms while cutting military costs.
</P>
<P>
During today's meeting, Yeltsin pointed out that Russia should
reduce defense spending to 3.5 or three percent of Gross Domestic
Product by 2000, down from the present five percent. "Russia cannot
afford such expense," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev, 59, had served as deputy chief of staff and later
deputy commander of the Strategic Missile Forces before taking the
commander's mandate in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
