<HEADLINE> Buddha's Birthday Celebrated in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Nepal today celebrated the
2,541th birthday of Lord Buddha, or Sakyamuni, amid an effort to
develop the birthplace of the founder of Buddhism to boost the
country's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand in a message called on
all of the nation to help develop Lumbini of West Nepal into an
international tourist and pilgrimage destination.
</P>
<P>
Chand also appealed to the people to join hands for building
the country under the Buddha's teachings of world peace, religious
harmony and coexistence.
</P>
<P>
Archaeological studies showed that Lord Buddha was born in
today's Lumbini, about 150 km west of Kathmandu, as a royal prince
of the ancient Sakya dynasty which existed 25 centuries ago in the
northern part of the Indian subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
A three-day Lumbini Festival opened today in the western Nepali
town as part of the government's effort to promote the Buddha's
birthplace as a pilgrimage center for Buddhists all over the
world.
</P>
<P>
Various activities including religious talk program, elephant
procession with Buddha statues, afforestation and worship sessions
were being organized during the event.
</P>
<P>
Nepali Buddhist scholars and local officials in Lumbini have
been urging the government to speed up the infrastructure
development in the small town and demanded an international
airport be built there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
