<HEADLINE> Inter-Korean Red Cross Talks on Aid to Resume Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL May 22 (Xinhua) -- Inter-Korean Red Cross talks will open
Friday in Beijing for a second round of negotiations on the
South's food aid to the North side.
</P>
<P>
Lee Byung-wung, Secretary-general of the South Korean Red
Cross, left for Beijing today to attend the talks with his
counterpart, Paek Yongho, of the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The meeting will discuss the scale, timing, type and procedures
for food aid delivery. The South is ready to announce grain
assistance of 50,000 tons by the end of July, say Red Cross
officials here.
</P>
<P>
The first round of talks was held earlier this month in Beijing
but ended without resolution after the South failed to notify how
and when it would deliver the food aid as demanded by the north.
</P>
<P>
The South earlier suggested Seoul or Pyongyang as the site of
talks but agreed on Tuesday with the North's belief they should be
reopened in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The South would reveal its plan for the grain aid, but would
stick to its former demands to establish land delivery routes,
such as through the truce village of Panmunjom, with its officials
participating in the distribution process.
</P>
<P>
Through the International Federation of Red Cross and Red
Cresent Societies (IFRC), the South Korean Red Cross has donated 3.9
million U.S. dollars worth of food and goods to the DPRK since November
1995, says its releases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
