<HEADLINE> Kabila's Troops Take Key Matadi Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KINSHASA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- President Laurent Kabila of the
Democratic Republic of Congo said his troops today took over the
seaport of Matadi, 400 km to the west of capital Kinshasa,
marking his control of all the territory of Africa's third
largest country.
</P>
<P>
"Matadi has just been liberated today," smiled 56-year-old
Kabila, who announced himself preisdent as he finally toppled
exiled president Mobutu Sese Seko's regime by his armed capture
of capital Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Matadi, the last strategic point to be taken over by Kabila's
people's liberation army, is important in that it is the import
and export lifeline of the virtually land-locked country.
</P>
<P>
The port links Democratic Congo's vast hinterland to the
Atlantic Ocean with a narrow, long strip of land.
</P>
<P>
Yesterday his spokesman said "the war is not over and fighting
is still going on," today Kabila marked another military victory
in the strategic port after fierce fighting between his troops
and armed forces loyal to Mobutu.
</P>
<P>
As one of his aides put it, "now we can safely say the
military war is over. But the war on the political and economic
fronts have just begun."
</P>
<P>
He said president Kabila now can focus his attention fully on
the formation of a new cabinet and on planning of the economic
reconstruction of the mineral-rich country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
