<HEADLINE> Immigration Is Linked to Unemployment: Australian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard today said he agreed with independent MP Pauline Hanson
that immigration and unemployment were linked but denied she had
forced his hand on cutting migrant numbers.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, who has been under pressure to renounce
Hanson's views on immigration since her maiden speech last
September, said he had believed the two were linked long before
she arrived on the political scene, the Australian Associated
Press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Hanson today claimed credit for the decision to cut migrant
numbers by 6,000 next year, saying she had forced the government
to take account of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
Howard said that while he agreed with Hanson that high
immigration was linked to high unemployment, she did not influence
his government's decision.
</P>
<P>
"I ... note that the rather empty populist who represents the
seat of Oxley, Mrs. Hanson, is running around going, 'Oh, I did
it,'" the prime minister was quoted as saying by the Australian
Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) Radio.
</P>
<P>
"Well, can I remind her and the rest of Australia that my
belief that there is a link between certain levels of immigration
and high unemployment goes back to 1991," the prime minister said
on an ABC night news program.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese-Australian, who specializes in Physics at a college
in Canberra, told Xinhua that the prime minister complained in the
late 1980s there were too many Asian immigrants in the country but
later offered apology to Asian voters during the last election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
The government Wednesday announced the immigration quota for
1997-1998 would be 68,000, 6,000 less than last year and a drop of
20 percent over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The decision brought cracks in conservative ranks, with
Victorian Premier Jeff Kennett saying the decision to cut the
intake was wrong and not in Australia's best interests.
</P>
<P>
Education Minister Amanda Vanstone told University of New
England students that Australia's future growth depends on
immigration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
