<HEADLINE> Manila Eyes Private Sector in Infrastructure Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is wooing
the private sector to play a bigger role in the country's
infrastructure construction.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a national infrastructure forum today, Finance
Secretary Roberto de Ocampo said the private sector participation
was "crucial" due to the colossal amount of infrastructure funds
needed.
</P>
<P>
According to the secretary, the country needs at least 40
billion U.S. dollars for infrastructure construction over the next
10 years, or 7 percent of its gross national product (GNP) every
year.
</P>
<P>
However, the country has the lowest expenses for infrastructure
in Asia at the present time, spending merely two percent of its
GNP while the figure stands at 7 percent in its neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
The private sector involvement is crucial due to limited
resources and as the government is gearing up to improve the
performance of its enterprises through privatization efforts, de
Ocampo said.
</P>
<P>
To lure the private sector to undertake infrastructure
projects, de Ocampo said, the government is establishing an
environment conducive to infrastructure privatization, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the government may also provide any form of
direct and indirect support, including cost sharing in which the
government could shoulder part of the expenses of the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
