<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- El-Op Electro-Optics Industries, one of Israel's
principal defense industry companies, has increased its presence
in South America, reported the English daily The Jerusalem Post
today.
</P>
<P>
The company has entered several upgrade projects for regional
air forces, said the report, quoting executives as saying
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The projects include a contract to supply a compact HUD
(head-up display) for the Pampa, the trainer for the Argentina Air
Force. The system is an electro-optical mechanism that
superimposes flight and sensor information on the pilot's forward
field of view.
</P>
<P>
Another HUD system has been supplied for the F-5 fighters in the
Chilean Air Force.
</P>
<P>
El-Op also supplied the HUD with Stroke-on-Raster mode
capability for the AMX fighter jet in the Brazilian Air
Force. The supply is part of the El-Op contract with the
Brizilian contractor Aeromot, which includes technology to that
company to manufacture and maintain the system.
</P>
<P>
The company, based in Rehovot near Tel Aviv, is currently
entering the upgrade project of the Brazilian ALX combat
trainer. El-Op has agreed to supply the airborne laser
range finder and designator, which increase the pilot's ability to
bomb targets by marking them with a laser guided bomb to the
target. The chief contractor for the upgrade is the Sao
Paulo-based Embrier.
</P>
<P>
El-Op is a private company owned by the Federman group. It
employs 1,800 people.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus and Slovakia has signed an agreement on
tourism to promote development of tourism between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
According to local press today, the agreement was signed here
Wednesday by Cypriot Minister of Commerce Industry and Tourism
Kyriakos Christofi and Slovak Minister of National Finance Karol
Cesnek.
</P>
<P>
The agreement provides for the simplification of traveling
procedures between the two countries, the promotion of
specialized tourism, such as conference, exhibition and sports, as
well as exchanges of youth groups.
</P>
<P>
Nicosia -- U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) will
provide assistance to a Cypriot national action plan for the
protection of forests, at an estimated cost of 215,000
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The relevant documents were signed here Wednesday by Cypriot
Agriculture, Natural Resources and the Environment Minister Costas
Petrides and FAO representative in Cyprus Amor Ben Romdhane.
</P>
<P>
The assistance program will cover the cost of consultancy
services to the forestry department for a specified period, in
aid of a National Action Plan on a forestry policy.
</P>
<P>
The Plan would deal with forestry development and management
on wood production.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's total official debt now stands at 6.4 billion
U.S. dollars, Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
This accounts for some 90 percent of its gross national
product, the English daily said.
</P>
<P>
From 3.5 billion to 4 billion dollars of the debt is owed to
bilateral official creditors with the rest concessional loans from
agencies like the World Bank and some Arab aid funds, said Deputy
Governor of the Central Bank of Jordan, Michel Marto, in an
interview with the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
