<HEADLINE> Taliban Shift Captured Opposition Generals to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Afghan Islamic militia Taliban
have shifted all leading opposition generals they arrested to
their southern headquarters Kandahar by helicopter, sources said
today.
</P>
<P>
The other prisoners of war are being shifted by road to
Kandahar, about 400 kilometers southwest of Kabul, said Taliban
sources in Peshawar, Pakistan's northwestern city,
</P>
<P>
All these generals and about 5,000 other prisoners of war will
be prosecuted in Islamic court in Kandahar for their war crimes,
they said.
</P>
<P>
Most of these generals and prisoners of war were arrested early
this week by Abdul Malik, the right-hand man of northern warlord
Rashid Dostum. Malik defected Monday to the Taliban's ranks taking
with him two provinces and allowing the Taliban to march into
another he had cut off.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who control more than two-thirds of Afghan
territory, launched a two-pronged offensive Tuesday making crucial
gains in central and northern Afghanistan.  
</P>
