<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Orders War Against Kidnappers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Defense Secretary Renato
de Villa said today that the government has declared an all-out
war against kidnap-for-ransom syndicates running rampant in the
country.
</P>
<P>
De Villa was referring to a recent directive by President Fidel
Ramos transferring the task of fighting kidnapping syndicates from
the police to the hands of the military.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with ranking military, police and civilian
officials in Cotabato city in Mindanao, De Villa promised that the
government will put more troops, expand operational coverage and
equip the troops with more firepower to fight kidnapping gangs.
</P>
<P>
He also rallied the civilian community for support in weeding
the military and police ranks of misfits and scalawags.
</P>
<P>
"We will also clean it (military and police) from inside while
we move and operate outside," De Villa declared, apparently
referring to reports that men in uniform were involved in crimes,
including kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
Kidnapping syndicates have been operating actively in the
southern Philippines recently, especially in western and central
Mindanao. During the past few months this year, at least 36
persons have been kidnapped in Cotabato city alone in western
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the business community in Cotabato city threatened
to stage a strike after a leading Filipino-Chinese businessman in
the city was killed by his captors.
</P>
<P>
The strike was averted after the government promised to meet
the businessmen's demands to intensify crackdown on kidnappers,
including the transfer of the anti-kidnapping task to the
military.  
</P>
</TEXT>
