<HEADLINE> Campaign Accidents Kill 126 in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- A total of 126 people have been
killed since Indonesia's election campaign started on April 27, an
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Most were killed in traffic accidents, Secretary General of the
General Election Committee Suryana Subrata said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, military sources said that more than 900 violent
incidents had taken place across the country during the campaign
period.
</P>
<P>
All the three contesting parties -- the ruling party Golkar,
the United Development Party (PPP) and the Indonesian Democratic
Party (PDI) have violated the campaign rules by conducting motor
parades and marches in the street, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The three parties will vie for 425 seats of the 500-member
Parliament with the remaining 75 seats reserved for the armed
forces who do not vote.
</P>
<P>
Friday will be last day of the campaign. The general election
will be held on May 29.
</P>
<P>
This time around, the country is divided into three groups of
campaign areas where the three parties could conduct their
campaigns in turn.
</P>
<P>
However, the supporters of the political parties violated the
campaign rules by showing strength in the streets. They attacked
each other by throwing stones and even setting fire to cars,
houses and other materials.
</P>
<P>
About 124 million voters are eligible to take part in the
general election, the sixth one in the country since 1971.
</P>
</TEXT>
