<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Syria Wins Gulf Support Against Turkey, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Syria has successfully won the
support from the Gulf countries for its drive against Turkey and
Israel during recent tours by its senior officials of the oil-rich
region, which ended in Bahrain today.
</P>
<P>
But the tours were marred by Syria's failure in Qatar to
persuade the country to suspend the planned 4th Middle East and
North Africa Economic Summit, which is scheduled to be held in
Qatar this November and will be attended by Israel.
</P>
<P>
In a diplomatic move embracing all of the member states of the
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC), Syria's vice President Abdul-Halim
Khaddam started his five-nation Gulf tour last week, which
included Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirate (UAE),
Oman, and Bahrain, while Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara
paid a visit to Qatar, another (GCC) state, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups six members states -- Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the
UAE, Qatar, Oman and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
The tours came following Turkish military incursion into
norther Iraq against its outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) and
its military pact signed with Israel, which has caused Syria's
concerns.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian senior officials' visits were also aimed at
discussing with the Gulf countries the latest developments in the
Middle East peace process, which has come to a halt due to
Israel's hardline policy as regards Jewish settlement expansion in
Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
A Syrian delegate accompanying Khaddam during his Gulf tour
said here Wednesday that Syria is trying to build a strong Arab
front against Turkey and Israel.
</P>
<P>
"We need a joint Arab stand against the threats and
challenges besetting the Arab nation. We are discussing (with
the Gulf states) the need for a strong stand in the face of the
hardline Israeli stances and the Turkish-Israeli alliance which
targets all of us," the official stressed.
</P>
<P>
Observers here maintain that Syria has succeeded in its
efforts. All the five countries visited by Khaddam have expressed
their support to Syria's stand in its peace negotiations with
Israel, saying a just and comprehensive peace in the Middle East
could never be achieved unless Israel commits itself to relevant
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials of the Gulf countries also said during their
meeting with the Syrian vice president that they support Syria's
stand on a resumption of peace talks with Israel from the point
where the two sides stopped.
</P>
<P>
Syrian-Israeli peace negotiations were suspended in February
1996 following a series of suicide bombings in Israel. Israel
demanded that Syria condemn the attacks as "terrorist activities,"
which was rejected by Syria.
</P>
<P>
After taking office in June, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu demanded the resumption of the talks begin without
precondition while Syria insisted that the talks should be
restarted on the basis of Israel's returning the Golan Heights to
Syria which it captured in 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Syria Wins Gulf Support Against Turkey, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Syria has also obtained the support from the Gulf countries for
its stand on Turkey's incursion into northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The UAE, Oman and Bahrain have urged, in their statements
during Khaddam's visits, Ankara to pull its troops out of the
mountainous areas in northern Iraq, stressing that such military
incursion has harmed Iraq's territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and Saudi Arabia also expressed their concerns over
Turkey's move and insisted that the Iraqi sovereignty be
preserved.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish troops, backed by the air force, have been chasing
rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in northern
Iraq in the past days, which has sparked strong international and
Arab criticisms.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Arab countries, including the GCC states, were also
concerned with Ankara's close military ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Oman, Khaddam said that the
Turkish-Israeli partnership threatens the entire Arab world as
well as peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
Despite clear response from the Gulf states on the
Israeli-Turkish military relations, informed sources said
officials of these countries said that they shared the same
concerns with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Shara paid an official visit to Qatari capital Doha Sunday in a
bid to dissuade Qatar from hosting the 4th Middle East and North
Africa Economic Summit in November, because Israel may attend the
gathering.
</P>
<P>
However, Fawaj al Attiyah, Qatari Foreign Ministry spokesman,
said after Shara's visit that "We will go ahead with it... ... It
is a purely economic forum and we expect Israel to participate in
it."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, however, said his country has not decided
whether to invite Israel to participate. "We expect Israel's
participation, but as you know, all these things are linked to
developments on the political front," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Israel has attended all of the three previous conferences,
which were separately held in  Casablanca of Morocco in 1994,
Amman of Jordan in 1995 and Cairo of Egypt in 1996.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Kuwait Monday, Khaddam said that such a
forum would violate Arab League's resolutions, which was a clear
criticism of Qatar's stand.
</P>
<P>
Any violation of Arab resolutions or economic cooperation with
Israel will inflict great harm on the Arab countries, the Syrian
vice president warned.
</P>
<P>
Qatar and Oman established economic contacts with Israel in
1995. But plans for expanding the relations have been put on hold
because of the strained Arab-Israeli relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
