<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges the Philippines to Stop Invading Chinese Territory (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government and people
will never accept the administrative rights the Philippines has
brazenly claimed on the Huangyan Island, Chinese Foreign Ministry
spokesman Shen Guofang stated at a weekly press conference here
today.
</P>
<P>
He demanded that the Philippine government halt immediately its
invasion of the Chinese territory to show respect to historical
facts, international laws, and China's sovereignty over the
Huangyan Island.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of April this year, the Philippine side has
dispatched warships and warplanes repeatedly to follow, monitor,
and interfere with an international amateur radio venture around
the island and adjacent sea area, which was sponsored by an
non-governmental Chinese organization and participated in by
amateur radio fans from China, the United States, and Japan, Shen
said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, he said, the Philippine side has also sent people
to land on the island several times to erect flagstaffs and
tablets, and unreasonably condemn Chinese personnel on the
island.
</P>
<P>
Shen noted that China has adopted a very restrained attitude
towards the above acts of the Philippines, proceeding from the
overall objective of maintaining Sino-Philippine friendship, and
has asked, through diplomatic channels, the Philippine side to
stop its intrusion of China's territory.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the recent development of the situation has
demonstrated that the Philippine side escalated its invasion of
the Huangyan Island by declaring the administrative rights over
the island claiming the Philippines'' 200-nautical-mile exclusive
economic zone as its excuse.
</P>
<P>
The Huangyan Island has been China's territory since ancient
times, and its legal status has long been defined, Shen said.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with Article 121 of the UN Convention on the Law
of the Sea, the Huangyan Island is the naturally-formed land area
which is surrounded by water on four sides and rises above the
surface of the sea at the high tide, rather than the shoal or
submerged reef that can not appear above the sea throughout the
year.
</P>
<P>
Many historical documents of China have recorded that China
enjoys sovereignty over the island, Shen said, adding that China
has officially named the island or changed its name three times,
which are the actions of a country exercising its sovereignty over
the island.
</P>
<P>
The international community has also recognized that the island
is China's territory. Many amateur radio fans have landed on the
island for explorations with the approval by the Chinese
government, and many countries are still applying for such
activities now, Shen noted.
</P>
<P>
He continued that as China's territory, the island has been put
on a DXCC call sign list for international amateur radio by a US
union of amateur radio.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine side has never expressed disagreement with
China's sovereignty claim over the island, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges Philippines to Stop Invading Chinese Territory (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Recently, Shen Guofang said, the Philippine side suddenly
declared maritime administrative rights on the Huangyan Island on
the pretext of its 200-nautical mile exclusive economic zone (EEZ).
</P>
<P>
This stance violates international law and the principles
formulated in the UN Convention on the Law of the Sea, as its
preface states explicitly that the maritime administrative rights
are not suitable to solving matters related to sovereignty, Shen
said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that according to the convention, coastal countries
only enjoy the right to explore and develop natural resources
within the EEZ, and the legal status of other countries'
territories should, by no means, be affected.
</P>
<P>
Shen stated that the issue of the Huangyan Island is that of
its sovereignty, while the development and utilization within the
EEZ belong to the maritime administrative rights.
</P>
<P>
The nature of these two issues, and the legal regulations they
apply, are completely different from each other and cannot be
mixed, he said, adding "the Philippine side is totally untenable
in its attempt to invade China's territory with its maritime
administrative rights.
</P>
<P>
Shen explained that the convention stipulates that under the
circumstance when related countries' EEZs are overlapping, it is
ineffective for a single country to declare the maritime
administrative rights on the 200-nautical mile EEZ.
</P>
<P>
The scope of the EEZs of China and the Philippines should be
mapped out through negotiations in line with principles of the
international law and rules, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government strongly urges the Philippine side to
respect the historical facts, international law, as well as
China's sovereignty over the Huangyan Island, and immediately stop
all its invasion activities on China's territory, in order to
safeguard peace and stability in the South China Sea and to
protect the overall state of the China-Philippines friendly
relations," Shen added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
