<HEADLINE> Sino-Pakistani Joint Team Establishes Camp at Nanga Parbat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Sino-Pakistani joint expedition
set up the first camp at the 8,125-meter-high Mount Nanga Parbat,
According to the Tibetan Mountaineering Association here today.
</P>
<P>
The joint expedition left Pakistan's capital Islamabad on May 7
and reached their base camp at the 4,100 meters on May 11.
However, their climbing activities were stopped for four days due
to a heavy snow which measured over one meter deep.
</P>
<P>
They started their climbing on May 18 and established the first
camp, preparing for their final assault in July.
</P>
<P>
Located at the western end of the Himalayas, Mount Nanga Parbat
has a speculiar geological structure and environment. It was
scaled for the first time in 1953 by the German and Austrian joint
team.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, a total of 62 climbers were dead in their attempting
to scale the peak, the 9th highest in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-Pakistani joint team is formed by 11 Tibetans and five
Pakistanis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
