<HEADLINE> Minister: Israeli Policy Undermines Peace March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
has warned that the Israeli policy seeking to impose a "rightist
Likudist supremacy" will lead to a collapse of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu's policy is not
conducive to any kind of peace as it has violated all principles
and international conventions, said Moussa in an interview
published today by the Egyptian Arabic daily newspaper Al Ahram.
</P>
<P>
He renewed the call for abiding by signed agreements and
stopping Israel's settlement building on Arab East Jerusalem, an
issue that has led to the halt of the peace process for two months.
</P>
<P>
Israel refuses to budge on its settlement building in Jerusalem
which it wants to have as future capital while the Palestinians
insist on stopping the project before resuming the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Moussa demanded the U.S. to deal with everything impeding the
peace process "positively and objectively," especially the Israeli
settlement policy in order to realize the balance required for
restarting the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he urged the Europeans to expand their so far
"limited role" and serve as a counter-balance to the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The matter requires interwoven efforts," he said, adding that
the European mediation alone cannot accomplish achievements, but
can unequivocally complement the U.S. efforts.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak held talks here Wednesday with
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat as the
deadlocked peace process shows no trace of a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
He proposed a six-month freeze on the construction of
settlements until negotiations open on the future of Jerusalem, an
idea designed to "set a moratorium on the building in order to
pave the way for meaningful negotiations," according to Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, which signed a peace deal with Israel in 1979, has been
one of the key mediators in the Mideast peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
