<HEADLINE> Manila, MILF Make No Progress in Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The fourth round of low-level talks
between the Philippine government and the Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF) ended in Cotabato City, the Southern Philippines,
today without any progress, but negotiators agreed to meet again
on June 17-18.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice-chairman for political affairs, said
the Government-MILF cessation committees failed to arrive at a
consensus on the issues under discussion, especially the
repositioning of respective combatants in Buldon, Maguindanao of
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
He said that the failure of the three-day talks was caused by
the government negotiators' back-tracking on their own proposal
for no armed zones and the creation of a joint peace-keeping force
in Buldon.
</P>
<P>
The government negotiators have requested the MILF to have a
more thorough study on their proposal, the rebel leader said.
</P>
<P>
Jaafar said that progress is expected in the scheduled fifth
round of dialogue next month.
</P>
<P>
The 12,000-strong MILF has become the country's major
anti-government group since Manila and the Moro National
Liberation Front signed an accord on peace in Mindanao last
September. The MILF is fighting for an independent Muslim state in
Mindanao.  
</P>
</TEXT>
