<HEADLINE> Iranian President Assures Voters of Fair Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani today inspected the election headquarters and assured
millions of voters of fair elections tomorrow, saying
"possibility of error in elections virtually nil."
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that the 64-year-old
president, who has to step down after serving two four-year terms
in the office, made a one-hour inspection of the election
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani said that steps taken by the Interior Ministry for
holding the 7th presidential elections have reduced the
possibility of error during the voting and counting to near zero.
</P>
<P>
He called on all executors and observers at the elections to
be extremely precise in conducting the nationwide presidential
elections slated for May 23.
</P>
<P>
This is the second statement by the Iranian president on the
issue of the vote rigging. Last Friday, Rafsanjani openly warned
Interior Ministry officials against any kinds of cheating at
ballot boxes and called for strict impartiality of election
observers.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to dispel the wide concern from the public about the
election fraud, Iranian Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei Wednesday
made a statement, pledging no vote rigging in the presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei said that three bodies -- the Interior Ministry, the
Guardians Council and himself -- will watch against any fraud in
the elections.
</P>
<P>
Addressing high-ranking officials and families of prisoners of
war and missing in action during the eight-year war between Iran
and Iraq (1980-1988), he assured the people of the whole country
by saying "I myself will be watchful and will not let any one
commit any fraud in the elections."
</P>
<P>
Conservative Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri and
open-minded former cultural and Islamic guidance minister
Mohammad Khatami are the two main contenders during the
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
The two rivals are represented by two major factions -- the
traditional and conservative camp backed by Ali Khamenei and the
moderate and liberal camp supported by Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
The victory of either presidential candidate would produce
different kind of political and economic impact upon the
political horizon in Iran, observers here noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
