<HEADLINE> Bonn-Tehran Economic Ties Normal After Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran said today that the Berlin
court ruling, which implicated top Iranian leaders behind the
Mykonos case, has not had much adverse effect on economic
relations between Bonn and Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made by Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar
Velayati in an interview with the Cable News Network (CNN) this
morning.
</P>
<P>
On future of Tehran-Bonn economic relations, he said, as
far as the European countries are concerned, they do not
intend to alter their policies.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, Iran plans to review its priorities in
economic relations with other countries.
</P>
<P>
Iran's relations with European countries have been brought into
a grave crisis and all ambassadors of 15 EU countries have been
recalled after the verdict of the Mykonos case by the Berlin court
on April 10.
</P>
<P>
Germany is the leading trade partner of Iran after the United
States broke off its diplomatic and economic ties with Tehran 18
year ago. The total annual trade volume of the two countries once
topped 4 billion U.S. dollars in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The EU countries take a lionshare of Iran's total import and
export. Their exports to Iran made up 41.3 percent of the total
import of Iran while their import from Iran made up 32.8 percent
of the total export of Iran in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The EU countries have occupied a majority of the Iranian
market, which imports about 15-18 billion dollars worth of
products from various of countries.
</P>
<P>
Velayati stipulated that what happened in Germany was a
disaster for the German judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Terming as strange and contrary to all judicial and
international principles the implication of Iran by the prosecutor
of Berlin Court, he said, no one has the right to judge about
high-ranking officials of other countries and come up with a
sentence.
</P>
<P>
If such a procedure becomes prevalent, no one can prevent
chaos in the world and every country will allow itself to
question and judge high-ranking officials of other countries in
its own courts. "Then we will have a jungle."
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister stressed that the recent developments in
Germany were due to pressures exerted by influential circles,
the Zionists in particular.
</P>
<P>
He also touched on the failure of critical dialog between
Iran and the European Union saying that prior to EU's decision
Iran had announced discontinuation of the talks on the grounds
they were not in the interest of Iran.
</P>
<P>
Asked if such a ruling was not issued in Germany, would Iran
had gone ahead with the dialog, he replied, "Tehran had made it
clear that it would not return to the negotiation table."
</P>
<P>
Suspension of the critical dialog between EU and Iran is one
of latest decisions made by the EU member states at the
ministerial meeting concluded in Luxembourg late last month.
</P>
<P>
The EU also decided to stop the ministerial level contact
between the two sides and continue its arm embargo on Iran as a
protest against Iran for the alleged order by the Iranian leaders
to assassinate four Kurdish leaders in a Berlin restaurant in
1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
