<HEADLINE> India's Scientific Council Flays U.S. Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- India's Council of Scientific and
Industrial Research (CSIR) has strongly objected to U.S.
ambassador to India Frank Wisner's threat to stop collaboration
with Indian scientists if India does not amend its patent law.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of CSIR said here today that conditionalities are
not desirable in science and technology agreements.
</P>
<P>
The science involves flow of knowledge which should be free of
any conditions and India expects other countries not to impose any
extra legal restrictions on it, he said.
</P>
<P>
Frank Wisner had warned at a joint meeting of Indian and
American officials on Tuesday that the future of Indo-U.S. science
and technology cooperation depended on how India resolved issues
like intellectual property rights which inhibit scientific
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. would be unable to negotiate a formal
science and technology agreement and some areas of research and
training would be closed to cooperation if India did not resolve
the issues.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held to work out a strategy for a new science
and technology agreement between the two countries as the existing
one ends in December this year.
</P>
<P>
The CSIR spokesman said that India scrupulously meets its
international obligations as evident from the large number of
collaborations between India and other countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
