<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: W. African Gas Pipeline Project Faces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- A gas pipeline project, aimed at
providing Benin, Togo and Ghana with Nigeria's gas and yielding
500 million U.S. Dollars in the first ten years, seems to be
facing threat by a recent Ghana-Cote d'Ivorie accord.
</P>
<P>
As the project cannot be completed as scheduled for 1998 due
to bureaucratic and political bottlenecks, the accord offers
Ghana gas from Cote d'Ivorie's Lion Gas Field for power supply.
No more details of the accord are known.
</P>
<P>
The project, with a cost of 260 million U.S. Dollars, has been
expected to transport some 50 million standard cubic feet gas
daily from gas-rich Nigeria to the western African countries
through pipeline.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting here Wednesday, Nigerian industrial leaders
expressed fears that the Ghana-Cote d'Ivorie accord may pose a
fresh threat to the project and thus weaken Nigeria's gas
industry and the regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Citing the importance of the project to both national and
sub-regional interest, the industrial leaders called on the
Nigerian government to encourage investment and give incentives
to investors concerned.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria should maintain its active role in investment
opportunities in oil and gas fields and in the cooperation in the
sub-region, Africa and the world, they urged.
</P>
<P>
They appealed to have the gas industry privatized so as to
record significant achievements in the construction of the
project.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, Ghana, Togo and Benin signed an agreement in
September 1995 for the construction, maintenance and operation of
the gas pipeline.
</P>
<P>
The gas pipeline is also expected to cover the entire western
African region around the turning of this century, according to a
plan of the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
A steering committee was later established comprising
ministers responsible or their representatives in these
countries, but later failing to coordinate the project funds from
various international sources.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the project owners have not been able to provide
funds and infrastructure necessary for the West African Pipeline
Company, established earlier this year by the four countries to
try to coordinate the project more effectively.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's crude oil and gas resources stand at 20 billion
barrels and 256,000 cubic feet respectively, making for 60 and 96
percent of Africa's potential.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the associated gas is largely being flared in oil
fields of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
