<HEADLINE> Philippine Military Denies Existence of Coup Plotters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- A senior Philippine military
official today denied the existence of a group of military coup
plotters, who have reportedly threatened to launch a coup against
the Ramos administration.
</P>
<P>
General Arnulfo Acedera, chief of the Philippine Armed Forces,
told reporters that there is no such group within the armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
"We do not recognize such group even if it really exists," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a group, claimed as "Filipino Soldiers for the
Philippines," issued a statement, saying it will stage a military
coup against the government if President Fidel Ramos will not
support Defense Secretary Renato De Villa's bid for the presidency
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers supportive of De Villa will launch a coup if Ramos
will not fully support or anoint the defense chief as the ruling
party's presidential candidate, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
De Villa, who intends to run for the presidency, has not joined
the ruling Lakas-NUCD (National Union for Christian Democrats),
and has not formally announced his bid for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Under the Philippine Constitution, President Ramos is serving a
single six-year term and is not allowed to seek re-election in the
1998 elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
