<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Pushed Deeper into Record Territory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Blue chip bank stocks surged again
today, pushing the Australian share market further into record
territory.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed at a new high of 2,547.9, a
rise of 4.7 points, and just off the day's trading high of
2,551.2.
</P>
<P>
"All the action was still in the resources and the banks,"
Austock Brokers' Oliver Messenger said, adding banks had benefited
this week from the decision by the U.S. Federal Reserve to leave
interest rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The banking index added 45.1 points, or 1.02 percent, to
4,478.0 with the standouts being National Australia Bank which
shot up 26.7 cents to 18.45 Australian dollars and Commonwealth
Bank, up 26 cents to 14.09 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The banks had another good run, all but ANZ which had a little
bit of profit-taking after a sensational run yesterday," Lance
Jones' Brett O'Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
Westpac shares rose seven to 7.24 Australian dollars while ANZ
lost one to 8.18 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index gained 4.3 points to 3,937.6 and the
all resources rose 5.6 to 1,486.3.
</P>
<P>
The gold index ended 1.8 points firmer at 1,544.7 while gold
bullion closed in Sydney at 343.45 US dollars an ounce from 343.10
US dollars at Wednesday's close.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 409.3 million shares traded valued at
725.3 million Australian dollars (558 million US dollars) with
rises outweighing falls 550 to 492.  
</P>
</TEXT>
