<HEADLINE> "Sightfirst" China Action Plan Initiated to Help the Blind </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- A project called "Sightfirst"
China Action Plan was sponsored here on Wednesday in a bid to
restore the eyesight of 1.75 million cataract patients on the
Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
The project will be undertaken jointly by the Hong Kong and
Macao Lions Club and the Chinese State Council's Coordinating
Committee on Disability for a period of five years, according to
local media reports today.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization's figures show that China has
more than nine million blind people, of which four million cases
were caused by cataracts.
</P>
<P>
However, due to limited resources, every year only about
200,000 patients are able to receive treatment.
</P>
<P>
The China Action Plan will receive 117 million HK dollars (15
million US dollars) from the Lions Club International and 1.2
billion HK dollars (153.85 million US dollars) in funding approved
by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
The project will send 250 medical teams to rural and
poverty-stricken areas in the Chinese mainland over the next five
years, and it will also train 4,000 ophthalmologists and 7,000
support staff.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
