<HEADLINE> Australia's Warning Against Visiting Macao Unreasonable: Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Macao government said on
Wednesday night that the warning from the Australian authorities
to its citizens against visiting Macao is "inappropriate and
unreasonable."
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the government Tourism Office said that
the Macao government has been informed by the Australian
authorities of its decision to give out a warning to its citizens
planning to travel to Macao.
</P>
<P>
"The warning from the Australian government is pointless,
inappropriate and unreasonable," said the statement. "The Macao
government has instantly expressed the position to the Australian
consulate."
</P>
<P>
The Australian government warns its citizens to "be careful"
when going sightseeing to Macao because of organized crimes in
Macao. But it does not prevent them from traveling to Macao,
according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the warning from the Australian
authorities may be a result of "exaggerated and distorted report
of foreign media."
</P>
<P>
"Those reports have given Macao a (bad) image," it said. "But
when people traveling to Macao they will find immediately that
their previous (bad) impression on Macao is wrong."
</P>
<P>
A wave of triad-related crimes hit the territory over the past
few months, causing at least 15 deaths and a dozen injuries.
The wave has temporarily calmed down.  
</P>
</TEXT>
