<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Inflation Rate Continues to Moderate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's consumer price
inflation rate continued to moderate in April, with the Composite
Consumer Price Index showing a year-on-year increase of 5.6
percent, lower than that of 5.9 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
The Composite CPI is compiled on the basis of the combined
expenditure pattern of all households, according to an official
release today.
</P>
<P>
Analyzed by component, faster year-on-year increases than the
overall average in April were recorded for clothing and footwear;
housing and miscellaneous goods. Meanwhile, those components with
slower year-on-year increases were durable goods; meals bought
away from home and transport.
</P>
<P>
Taking the first four months together, the increases in the
Composite CPI averaged at 6.0 percent, according to the release.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
