<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Muslim Leader to Deliver Region Address </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The rebel-turned governor of the
Philippines' Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao (ARMM), Nur
Misuari, will deliver an address on May 26 on his performance
since taking office last October, the Philippine News Agency said
today.
</P>
<P>
The much-awaited state of the region address, originally slated
for April 28, was postponed due to a big blaze which gutted a
hotel in Cotabato city, capital of Maguindanao province and the
seat of Misuari's office, on April 26.
</P>
<P>
The fire killed 27 people, some of whom were guests invited to
attend the Mindanao Regional Legislative Assembly meeting to
listen to Misuari's speech. The cause of the fire is still under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
Misuari's address will also focus on the achievement,
particularly in the economic area, made by the Southern Philippine
Council for Peace and Development which was also chaired by
Misuari.
</P>
<P>
The council was formed to push the development of southern
Philippines in line with a peace agreement signed last September
between the government and the MNLF.
</P>
<P>
The landmark peace accord ended the 28-year-old war launched by
the MNLF for an independent Islamic state. Misuari, MNLF chairman,
was later elected governor of the ARMM in an election held in
Muslim Mindanao in accordance with the accord.  
</P>
</TEXT>
