</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolian Grasslands Getting Closer To Outside World (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Years ago, the well-known Chinese
folk song writer Wang Luobin picked up a song, which he re-wrote
with the words: "In that remote place, there's a good girl,"
giving people a taste of the beauty of a pastoral landscape and an
impression that it was far away from ordinary life.
</P>
<P>
Today, however, the grasslands referred to in that song, what
with the development of modern transportation and
telecommunications, do not seem quite so remote any more.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Bade Ma Surong, a herdsman in the Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region in north China, seemed quite at home talking
about "cloned sheep", a strange new topic elsewhere in the world,
even though he lives in a felt tent in the midst of the Hulun Buir
Grasslands.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of miles away, in a little village that holds 50
pastoral households in the Tengger Desert in the western part of
Inner Mongolia, all the families can receive television programs
from southern China.
</P>
<P>
Improvements in modern telecommunications and transportation
facilities and the growing economic contacts with other parts of
China and elsewhere have reduced the physical space and
psychological distance between the grasslands and the outside
world, one local scholar says.
</P>
<P>
"The herdsmen no longer feel unfamiliar with the outside world,
and people from the outside world have more ways of getting to
know life on the grasslands. Therefore, the gap between the remote
grasslands and the outside world has been narrowed," said Pan
Zhaodong, a research fellow with the Inner Mongolia Branch of the
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia sprawls across a 1.18-million- sq.km. area in
northern China, and is the longest and narrowest autonomous region
running from east to west in China.
</P>
<P>
The grasslands were considered remote because of the lack of
communications and the inconvenience in travelling, and the lack
of development in the past. As a result, local people had little
chance to have any contact with the outside world, Pan
explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolian Grasslands Getting Closer To Outside World (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It was only 50 years ago when horses were the sole means
of getting to the pastoral areas from outside. But, since the
founding of the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region in 1947, travel
and communications have improved significantly, and digital and
program-controlled long-distance telephones are commonplace in
pastoral households. The installed telephone capacity is more than
1.2 million lines in the region.
</P>
<P>
The modern communications technology of mobile phones and
beepers, satellites and optical fibers are in wide use. By the end
of July, all townships in Inner Mongolia will have access to
phones.
</P>
<P>
In January, radio and television programs reached the whole of
Inner Mongolia, Herdsmen living deep in the grasslands could
get nearly 20 TV channels, some of which arrive bilingually in
both Mongolian and Chinese.
</P>
<P>
In Inner Mongolia these days, there are 50,000 km of highways
linking 90 percent of the townships. There are airports in the
cities of Huhhot, Hailar, Baotou and Xilinhot, linking Inner
Mongolia with more than 20 cities in other parts of the country,
as well as Hong Kong and two cities in Mongolia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
All this has greatly changed people's lives, an official with
the regional people's government says. Most herdsmen have left the
nomadic life and have settled down, with some having opened
businesses in other parts of the country, or abroad even.
</P>
<P>
"If you talk with the herdsmen who wear jeans, ride
motorcycles, and have a mobile phone in their hands, you will
sense how big the change is," the official noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
