<HEADLINE> Impact of U.S. Sanctions Limited: Thai Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Thai Foreign Ministry spokesman
Surapong Jayanama said that it is unlikely the U.S. economic
sanctions on Myanmar would pressure ASEAN to defer its decision on
the admission of Myanmar, Cambodia and Laos.
</P>
<P>
he said, "ASEAN has always said that its decision to admit
Myanmar along with Laos and Cambodia would not be affected by
outside pressure," according to a report in the Nation today.
</P>
<P>
He said that in fact U.S. president Bill Clinton's executive
order on the economic sanctions could be counter-productive as it
could push ASEAN into pressing ahead with its decision just to
save face.
</P>
<P>
Last year, leaders of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) decided to let the three Southeast Asian countries
to join the grouping simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
However, last month the U.S. government sent out message that
it would not like to see Myanmar join ASEAN on the grounds of the
country's "woeful" human rights record.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the U.S. sanction order, Surapong said the impact
on Myanmar would be "only limited" as American companies already
investing in Myanmar would not be affected.
</P>
<P>
He also said that some European countries are disturbed by the
U.S. decision and prepared to file complaints with the World Trade
Organization for the U.S. attempt to link non-trade issues (human
rights and democracy) with trade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
