<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China Cotton Attracting Chinese And Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Fu Jiankang, a 24-year-old native of
Sichuan, travelled 5,000 km in 1991 from his home in southwest
China to the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region in the northwest to
get a piece of land to grow cotton.
</P>
<P>
Within seven years, the land on which he had a contract had
grown from 0.6 ha to seven ha, 40 times the size of the plot of
ground he had tilled in his native home.
</P>
<P>
"In each of the past six years, I earned 100,000 yuan, the
equivalent of the combined income of my family for four years," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"I will invest 70,000 yuan, 50 times the annual income of a
Chinese farmer, on my field this year," he added.
</P>
<P>
When asked why he came to Xinjiang, Fu explained that
agriculture in the region is highly mechanized and encourages
individuals sign contracts to open up farmland.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Chinese farmers like Fu have come a long way from
home to Xinjiang to get involved in cotton cultivation.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang produced an average of 900,000 tons of cotton each of
the past three years, accounting for a quarter of the national
total. And it has turned 433,300 ha of uncultivated land into
fertile farmland with three billion yuan provided by a dozen other
provinces.
</P>
<P>
Last September, the regional government opened 466,600 ha of
wasteland to overseas investors. Israel, Canada, the United States
and Hong Kong have all shown a great deal of interest.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has provided 375 million US dollars in loans for
an agricultural project in the Tarim Basin, the largest
agricultural loan ever provided by the World Bank in China.
</P>
<P>
John Weatherhogg, an agro-economist of the Food and Agriculture
Organization of the United Nations, said that Xinjiang has great
potential for developing its cotton industry and that now is a
good time to invest.
</P>
<P>
A local agriculture official said the region is building a
66,600-ha cotton production base at a cost of 9.4 billion yuan,
and that both domestic and overseas investors are welcome. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
