<HEADLINE> African Tourism Meeting to Be Held in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The first African Tourism
Conference will be held in Nairobi in September as part of an
Africa Travel Market Week to be celebrated throughout Sub-Saharan
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The local daily newspaper East African Standard today reported
that the meeting would provide a vital educational forum for
delegates to discuss current and future trends in inbound and
outbound travel in Sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which is scheduled to take place immediately prior
to the African Travel Market in Johannesburg, South Africa, is
designed to enhance the existing programs in the region and help
draft strategies to assist the emerging market.
</P>
<P>
Subjects to be discussed at the meeting will cover conference
business opportunities, business travel in Africa, misconceptions
of Africa, marketing of regional tourism and media in promotion
of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Tourism Minister Protus Momanyi was quoted as saying
that there was need for tourism destinations like Kenya and
Africa as a whole to redouble their efforts in tourism promotion
and marketing as Africa accounted for only a mere 1.2 percent of
the world volume of tourism flow.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the Executive Council meeting of the World
Tourism Organization, which ended yesterday in Philippines, that
Africa also needed to diversify tourism products and tourist source
markets in order to maximize the industry's benefits to the
people.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's tourism industry accounts for 37 percent of the
national total foreign exchange earnings and caters for the
employment of 9.1 percent of the total wage earners.
</P>
<P>
The tourism industry in Kenya has evolved to become number one
single exchange earner ahead of coffee and tea which are the
leading export earners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
