<HEADLINE> Liberian Elections Postponed to July 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Presidential and parliamentary
elections in Liberia set for May 30 this year has been
rescheduled to July 19.
</P>
<P>
The Committee of Nine on Liberia of the Economic Community of
West African States (ECOWAS) made the decision at an
extra-ordinary summit in Abuja on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the inauguration of the new government was
shifted to August 2.
</P>
<P>
In the event of a run-off, elections are to be held on August 2,
while the inauguration of the new government will be on August 16.
</P>
<P>
The one-day summit also approved a budget of 5.2 million US
Dollars for the elections, with 700,000 dollars for personnel and
administrative cost and 4.7 million dollars for technical cost.
</P>
<P>
The summit decided that a minimum of 1.5 million dollars will be
sourced from the west Africa sub-region, with each of the 16 ECOWAS
member countries contributing at least 100,000 dollars in cash.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS Chairman and Nigerian Head of State General Sani Abacha
proposed at the summit that after accomplishing its mission in
Liberia, the ECOWAS monitoring group known as ECOMOG be transformed
into the nucleus of a sub-regional permanent peace-keeping force.
</P>
<P>
The reactions of other leaders at the summit were not known at the
moment.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, the ECOMOG now has about 11,000 soldiers,
with Nigeria still contributing the largest number of troops.
</P>
<P>
The postponement of the Liberian elections was at the request of 11
liberian parties who cited the security situation, the lack of voters'
education, among others as their reasons. enditem

