<HEADLINE> China's Tourism Growth Rate Surpassing National Economy's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The tourism industry in China has
grown at an annual rate of 22.6 percent over the past 18 years,
five percentage points higher than that of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Wendong, vice chairman of China National Tourism
Administration, told a national conference on duty-free business
which opened yesterday in Beijing that, for the past 18 years,
China's foreign exchange earnings from tourism showed a 38-fold
increase, to 10.2 billion US dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"China's tourism and travel industry have retained their
growth, with tourists from all over the world, and double-digit
growth last year," Cheng said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese central and local governments are
placing great importance on the business, with many areas listing
it as a "pillar" or a "dragon head".
</P>
<P>
On the industry's prospects, Cheng said that work will
concentrate on raising the scale and quality of tourism to make it
a major part of the national economy and to turn China into a
major tourist country by the beginning of the 21 century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
