<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 08:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Parliament Postpones Approval of State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's parliament has said
the government's ambitious revenue boosting plan contained in the
1997-98 budget is unconstitutional, officials sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The Finance and Economics Affairs Committee of the Kuwaiti
National Assembly postponed the approval of the budget at a
session last night.
</P>
<P>
The committee told the government that the plan to boost
non-oil revenuers by over 200 million Kuwait dinars (660 million
U.S. dollars) through charges and taxation violated the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
By law, the government is not allowed to raise charges on
public services without any parliamentary approval.
</P>
<P>
It said the projected increase also runs counter to the
Charges Freeze Law which was issued by the previous parliament
in 1995 and bans any increase in the public charges beyond its
DPA158WSD031S22PEQL17:0817:080521
level on December 31, 1994.
</P>
<P>
The government has submitted a bill two months ago asking the
National Assembly to change the Charges Freeze Law for all
services except electricity and water.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaitis enjoy a cradle-to-grave welfare system that offers
free education and health care and heavily-subsidized state
services such as electricity and water.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, the Kuwaiti government proposed a 4.37
billion dinars (14.42 billion dollars) budget expenditure and 3.2
billion dinars (10.56 billion dollars) revenues for the fiscal
year of 1997-98 starting from this July 1, with a net deficit of
1.17 billion dinars (3.86 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The 3.2 billion Kuwait dinars revenues projected in the fiscal
year draft budget include a projected oil revenues of 2.56
billion dinars (7.67 billion dollars) at an estimated selling
price of 13 dollars per barrel. Oil exports account for around 80
percent of the state income.
</P>
<P>
The budget also proposed to increase non-oil revenues by more
than 40 percent during the coming fiscal year, generating as
much as 645 million dinars (2.128 billion dollars) from
non-oil sources, mainly the increase and imposition of charges and
fees on public services.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti cabinet approved the draft law, calling on the
National Assembly to allow ministries to impose new charges and
increase the existing ones on public services in February. The
draft budget also has to be approved by the head of the state
before it becomes law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
