<HEADLINE> Tourism Becoming Important for Chinese Industrial Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The northeastern Chinese city of
Shenyang has decided to spend 10 million yuan (1.2 million US
dollars) each year on tourism, as it becomes an important business
for this old industrial base and provincial capital of Liaoning.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang is rich in natural resouces and tourist attractions,
but tourism revenues now only account for a meager four percent of
the city's GNP. This does not reflect its status as a major city,
city officials say.
</P>
<P>
In its latest move to boost tourism and the travel industry,
the city has decided to spend money renovating a number of
historical sites like the Shenyang Palace Museum and the Northern
and Eastern Tombs.
</P>
<P>
The money will also be spent on new attractions like the
Shenyang Amusement Park, the Strange Slope, and Xinmin Minor West
Lake.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will also be made to jointly develop scenic spots and
design tourist routes with the neighboring cities of Anshan,
Fushun and Benxi.
</P>
<P>
The city has over 150 institutions directly involved in tourism
and had over 100,000 overseas tourists last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
