<HEADLINE> Japanese FM Leaves for Visit to Russia, Britain, France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Foreign Minister Yukihiko
Ikeda left for Moscow today to start a three-nation tour which
also includes Britain and France.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day stay in Moscow, Ikeda will hold talks on
bilateral and international issues with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin and Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov, Kyodo News quoted
government sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ikeda's trip to Moscow is expected to help lay the groundwork
for an exchange of visits by the leaders of the two countries
before the end of this year, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The trip will also promote dialogue to help resolve the
long-standing territorial dispute over four Russia-held islands
off Japan's northeastern Hokkaido, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese foreign minister will make preparations for the
Group of Seven summit next month in Denver, when Russia will be
joining the body as a full member for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and Yeltsin are
scheduled to hold talks there.
</P>
<P>
In London, Ikeda will hold talks with new British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook, Japanese Foreign Ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
He will attend a ministerial meeting of the Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) and hold talks with
his South Korean and French counterparts Yoo Chong ha and Herve de
Charette in Paris before returning home May 29. 
