<HEADLINE> Large Income Increase Registered in North Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Per capita income of residents of
Tianjin, a leading port city in north China, had the highest
growth of the four big Chinese cities of Beijing, Shanghai,
Tianjin and Guangzhou, in 1996, according to a recent survey.
</P>
<P>
Per capita income in 1966 in Tianjin grew 19.43 percent last
year from the previous year, while the increase in Shanghai was
17.34 percent; Beijing, 13.18 percent; and Guangzhou, 9.66 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, China's largest financial center, people spent
more money on stocks than in the three other cities, according to
the Shanghai Economic Bureau.
</P>
<P>
In Guangzhou, the capital of south China's Guangdong Province,
people spent an average of 1,056 yuan per person annually dining
out, accounting for a quarter of their total annual food
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
The people of Beijing spent much more on clothing, with per
capita spending reaching 874 yuan annually, compared to average
expenditures of around 590 yuan in Shanghai, Guangzhou and Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Residents in Shanghai spent only 97 yuan on housing rent per
capita annually, only a third of that in Guangzhou and two-thirds
of that in Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
