<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expecting 10 Percent Economic Growth in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- China's economic growth rate in
1997 is expected to be around 10 percent, with price increases
being held to around five percent, according to Qiu Xiaohua, chief
economist with the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
In analyzing China's advantages and disadvantages in economic
development, Qiu told a seminar in Beijing on Wednesday that China
maintained rapid economic growth in the first four months of this
year, with an 11.4 percent year-on-year increase in industrial
output, and a rise of only 2.3 percent in retail prices. The GDP
rose by 9.4 percent during the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Exports increased 26.9 percent, while imports dropped 0.5
percent during the four-month period, and China's international
payments are improving, and the financial situation is basically
normal.
</P>
<P>
In the second half of last year, China's economic performance
had another period of stable development, and the upward trend
will go further this year, Qiu said, attributing the rapid growth
and stable prices to macro-economic controls, the improved
relation of supply and demand, and successful price control in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The bottleneck in China's economic development has been
markedly improved thanks to large-scale construction of basic
industries and infrastructure, and less uncontrolled production in
the past few years, he said, noting that the stable international
situation and increasing world trade are favorable to China's
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Priority should be given to controlling fixed asset investment,
the money supply, and agriculture, as well as the structural
adjustment and enterprise reforms, to maintain a longer period of
stable economic growth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Economic Powerhouse Pushing Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, May 22 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong Province,
one of the most developed areas in China, is increasing efforts to
make its agriculture more efficient and more market-oriented.
</P>
<P>
It increased the output value of commercial farm products from
14 billion yuan in 1995 to more than 80 billion yuan last year,
and now two-thirds of its farm produce is sold elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
It also has more than 4,000 farm markets that have helped
increase the commodity rate of agriculture to over 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
It has established more than 5,000 farm produce bases, covering
about 2.6 million ha of cultivated land. High-quality rice paddies
take up more than 70 percent of that.
</P>
<P>
The province has a large number of chicken and animal breeding
farms, with 30 species of animals bred on a large scale.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture-related enterprises have greatly helped the scale
of operation and integration of trade and industry with
agriculture. The Guangdong Jinman Group Company, for example, is
helping 30 townships raise eels and has become one of the biggest
eel producers in the world, with a total annual output worth 1.5
billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
