<HEADLINE> Pakistan Not to Interfere in Afghan Issue: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 22 (Xinhua) -- "Pakistan continues to adhere to
its policy of non-interference in the internal affairs of all
countries including Afghanistan," a spokesman from the Foreign
Ministry said here today.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the latest development in Afghanistan at a weekly
press briefing, the spokesman said that the rebellion led by
General Abdul Malik has indicated a deep division within General
Rashid Dostum's National Islamic Movement.
</P>
<P>
He said that Pakistan hoped to see the restoration of durable
peace and stability in Afghanistan through the process of an
intro-Afghan dialogue which can lead to the establishment of a
broad-based government representing all Afghan factions.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the present development in Afghanistan will lead
the establishment of such a government generally accepted," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also said that Pakistan is not only interested in
peace in Afghanistan, but also in the fact that it would like more
than one million Afghan refugees still in Pakistan to go back home
safely.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Pakistan's Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan's
on-going visit to the United States, the spokesman said that the
visit is going on "very successfully".
</P>
<P>
He noted that Gohar Ayub Khan has had a "very useful and
productive meeting" with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright and other high-ranking U.S. government officials.
</P>
