<HEADLINE> China's Largest Coal Port to Increase Its Capacity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINHUANGDAO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Qinhuangdao port in north
China, the world's largest coal port, is expected to increase its
annual coal handling capacity to 100 million tons when the fourth
phase of its expansion is completed in July.
</P>
<P>
The port handled a total of 83.12 million tons of cargo in
1996, including 65 million tons of coal and 11 million tons of
crude oil.
</P>
<P>
The fourth phase of expansion, which includes importing
equipment from Japan, started in June of 1993, and is expected to
cost more than a billion yuan. It will increase the port's
handling capacity by 30 to 40 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Qinhuangdao is an important energy export port, mainly shipping
coal from China's largest coal base in Shanxi Province, in the
north, down the coast to energy-hungry southern provinces. It also
exports 20 million tons of coal to other countries annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
