<HEADLINE> Philippines, Malaysia to Launch Border Patrol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines and Malaysia will
hold the third Joint Coordinated Border Patrol Operations along
the common sea borders of both countries from May 24 to June 3,
the Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Ships and airplanes from both countries will participate in the
six-day exercise dubbed PHILMAL III and review the Standard
Operating Procedures of the Philippine-Malaysia Border Patrol
Coordinating Group.
</P>
<P>
Southern Command Chief of Philippine Armed Forces Romeo
Padiernos will lead top Philippine military officials in the
operations which start in Sandakan, Sabah, Malaysia, on May 24,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysians will also be in the southern Philippine city of
Zamboanga on June 3 for the closing ceremony of the joint border
patrol operations.
</P>
<P>
The exercise will include actual sea patrols by vessels of both
countries along the border to conduct simulated checks on vessels
crossing the border both ways.
</P>
<P>
Next week's border operations is the third to be conducted by
the two countries, the report said. The second one was held a year
ago with the opening ceremonies held in Zamboanga and the closing
ceremony in Sandakan.
</P>
<P>
The two countries' joint border operations started in November
1995, after the Philippine-Malaysia Joint Commission for Bilateral
Cooperation agreed to establish the Joint Committee on Border
Cooperation in December 1993.
</P>
<P>
So far, the two countries have evolved a system of coordination
with each other along the sea border particularly against sea
pirates, illegal entrants and other unlawful activities on the
high seas, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
