<HEADLINE> China Halting Random Charges for Overseas-funded Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Anshan, an industrial city in
northeast China, has asked institutions that collect fees from
overseas-funded enterprises to fill in forms so that it can put a
stop to the practice of random charging.
</P>
<P>
The collectors have to state the item, the regulation, the
time, the amount and their names on a "fee charging supervisory
card" for any charges like funds, membership fees, or insurance
premiums, according to a recent decision by city authorities.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made following a study by the city government
which found that while most of the 187 fees being charged were
reasonable, there were problems with unauthorized charges or
overcharging.
</P>
<P>
In order to protect the interests of overseas-funded
enterprises, the city government has defined 149 items as being
reasonable for payment and has urged putting a halt to any
unreasonable charges.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises are also encouraged to refuse payment of any
unreasonable fees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
