<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA Warns against Bribe Attempts at World Youth Tourney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 22 (Xinhua) -- FIFA have warned organisers of
the world youth soccer championship in Malaysia next month to
guard against attempts to bribe players.
</P>
<P>
The warning came after attempts to fix the same event in Qatar
two years ago by Southeast Asian syndidates. Three of five people
were caught came from Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"If it can happen in Qatar it can happen here," said Asian
Football Confederation general secretary Peter Velappan, who is
also the FIFA's ground inspections representative for the
tournament from June 18 to July 5.
</P>
<P>
Velappan added: "To check match fixing we have to be extra
vigilant. The local organising committee will have to work closely
with the police and team officials at the respective venues to
draw up some guidelines to keep track of the bookies."
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, over 100 players and officials were banned from
football by FIFA after being caught in one of the biggest match
fixing scandals in football.
</P>
<P>
There were also attempts by Malaysian bookies to fix matches in
last year's Tiger Cup in Singapore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
