<HEADLINE> Harvest to Drop by 50 Percent In Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's food and cash
crops production, particularly cotton and coffee, will decrease
by 50 percent this year due to severe drought.
</P>
<P>
Governor of Bank of Tanzania (BOT) Idris Rashidi said this
when meeting with Finnish business delegation recently.
</P>
<P>
He said proper measures were being taken to avert
economic problems, assuring people of enough food supply in the
wake of this alarming situation.
</P>
<P>
He said that as the economy has grown by four percent,
Tanzania should struggle to balance its trade.
</P>
<P>
Rashidi noted that the level of imports was 50 percent less
than what was expected.
</P>
<P>
"BOT was struggling to make sure that government expenditure
matches revenue collected to avoid borrowing from banks", he
said.
</P>
<P>
In order to liberalize the banking system, Rashidi said 16
financial institutions have been licensed to operate in Tanzania
and BOT has remained as supervisor and regulator of the banking
system.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government-owned National Bank of Commerce
(NBC) was currently undergoing major restructuring which is to
eventually lead to its privatization.
</P>
<P>
"NBC will be split into three organs within it there will be a
trade bank, a corporate bank and a micro-finance bank. This is to
lead into big competition with foreign banks coming to invest in
Tanzania", Rashidi added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
