<HEADLINE> Turkish Troops Plan to Remain in Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Turkish security forces will not
pull out of northern Iraq until the region is swept free of the
rebels of the Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), senior military
sources said here.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News today quoted the sources as saying
"The planned end of the operation is August. Until then we plan to
totally clear the region from the PKK terrorists, demolishing all
PKK camps and completely cutting logistic support."
</P>
<P>
The sources said Turkey will also "strongly urge" Iraq's
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) leader Jalal Talabani, who is
controlling an area near Iran's border with Iraq, not to support
the PKK in the region and also ask to provide stability in the
region in favor of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported that Syria,
which gives the biggest support to the PKK organization, has
built up troops at the northern Iraqi border by using the
excuse of a military exercise.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Iraq have also reportedly amassed forces around
the area of focus, which was carved out of northern Iraq as
a safe haven for Kurds.
</P>
<P>
The operation, which was launched on May 14, has drawn
criticism from the United Nations, western countries and
especially the Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The United Arab Emirates and Syria said Wednesday in a
joint statement that they were deeply concerned over the Turkish
military incursion in northern Iraq and urged Ankara to pull
its troops out of the region.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a near 13-year-old separatist war
which has claimed over 23,000 lives in eastern and southeastern
Turkey since August 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
