<HEADLINE> Israeli President to Meet with Mubarak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman
is expected to meet with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in the
next few days in an effort to break the deadlock in the Mideast
peace process, Israel Radio reported this morning.
</P>
<P>
Weizman and Mubarak discussed the stalemate in the peace
negotiations over a telephone call on Wednesday night, and agreed
to meet in the coming days to find a new formula to renew the
talks.
</P>
<P>
Weizman's Director-General Arye Shumer told Israel Radio that
the meeting will probably be held in Egypt, but added that
details of the planned meeting have not been finalized yet.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday night, Weizman also called Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu to inform him of the telephone conversation,
initiated by Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu later summoned Mohammed Bassiouny, the Egyptian
ambassador to Israel, and asked him to convey a message to
Mubarak, calling on Egypt to show positive interventions in the
diplomatic moves.
</P>
<P>
Reports here revealed that the European Union (EU) sources had
told Israel that Egypt was preparing a new initiative for both
the Palestinian and Syrian tracks in the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials said that United States special Middle East
coordinator, Dennis Ross attempted to bring together all the
different peace initiatives during his next visit to the region.
</P>
<P>
Ross is also expected to make a public call on both the
Israelis and Palestinians to renew their peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between the two sides stalled again in March
after Israel started building a controversial new Jewish
neighborhood at Har Homa (Jabal Abu Ghoneim) on the southeastern
outskirts of Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want as their
future capital.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have said that Israel must stop the
construction before talks can resume, while Israel is insisting
that the Palestinian National Authority must crack down on
extremist activities to reestablish full security
cooperation. 
</P>
