<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Attains Self-sufficiency in Cotton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- India has attained
self-sufficiency in cotton with production crossing the 16-million
bales mark in 1996-97, a government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
A five-fold increase in production had been recorded from
1949-50 onwards, when it stood at 2.75 million bales to about 16
million bales in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
The area under cotton cultivation had simultaneously risen from
4.93 million hectares to about 8.8 million hectares.
</P>
<P>
India has been able to export 0.5 to 1.5 million bales of
cotton annually, which was more than 22.5 percent of the total
export revenue.
</P>
<P>
Productivity had increased from about 87 kg to about 299 kg per
hectare, accompanied by an increase in the area of crop under
irrigated conditions from 2 percent in 1950 to about 31 percent in
the late 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The productivity level, however, did not compare favorably with
some of the other cotton growing countries. The productivity would
have to be stepped up from 300 kg to 400 kg of cotton per hectare
to meet the country's demand of 19 million bales by the year 2000,
the same official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian PM's Nepal Visit to Be Objective-Oriented </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar
Gujral's upcoming visit to Nepal, unlike that in the past, will be
meaningful and objective-oriented, a foreign affairs expert here
said today.
</P>
<P>
Gujral's visit, expected in the first week of June, will help
develop a "model relation" between the two countries in a
"concrete" manner, the official daily the Rising Nepal quoted a
senior Nepali diplomat as saying.
</P>
<P>
The first visit to Nepal by an Indian prime minister since 1992
is expected to thrash out ways to strengthen bilateral economic
ties, especially cooperation in water resources, tourism and
industry, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
According to Yadav Kant Silwal, former general secretary of the
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC), Gujral's
visit would help form a new dimension in Nepal-India relations and
promote Nepal's opportunities for joint investment and trade
activities.
</P>
<P>
Gujral's predecessor H. D. Deve Gowda earlier canceled his
scheduled Nepal visit twice in November 1996 and March 1997
respectively due to his mother's death and the change of
government here.
</P>
<P>
As to the Bhutanese refugee problem, on which India has always
refused Nepal's demand for its mediation, Silwal said India should
be asked to play an active role instead of a mediator in the
solution of the lingering issue. India handles foreign and defense
affairs for Bhutan.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100,000 Bhutanese, mostly of Nepalese origin, have been
living in eastern Nepal since 1990 when they were forced under
Bhutan's Ethnic cleansing policy to fled to Nepal via the Indian
territory.
</P>
<P>
During Gujral's visit, the documents about a landmark treaty on
the integrated development of the Mahakali border river between
the two countries will be exchanged, Nepali Foreign Secretary
Kumar Gyawali said.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali parliament last September ratified the Mahakali
treaty, under which the two countries will jointly launch a
6,480-megawatt multi-purpose hydro project on the border river,
about 450 west of Kathmandu.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Among Top 3 Investment Draws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- India has emerged as the world's
third most preferred destination for foreign direct investment
(FDI) in the medium term of five to ten years, behind only China
and the United States, said the World Economic Forum in its Global
Competitiveness Report 1997.
</P>
<P>
Apart from China and the U.S., India has emerged as a top
choice as an investment location mainly because of its market size
and expectations of further liberalization of capital movement
across its border, improvement in domestic institutions and
rationalization of economic policies to foster a favorable climate
for multinational companies, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"The opening up of vast countries such as China and India has
provided unprecedented opportunities for investors from advanced
industrial and newly industrialized countries to seek better
returns by investing in those capital-starved, emerging market
economies," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The expansion of FDI in these markets was caused by their
commitment to market-oriented structural reform, which has
improved the trade and investment climate and raised the expected
rate of return on capital in those countries, the report further
said.
</P>
<P>
The flow of FDI increased rapidly during the 1990s and its
level in the emerging markets grew by more than 170 percent from
1991 to 1995, while investment in the advanced industrial
countries increased by less than half that rate, the report added.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
