<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Party Leader Visits Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- General Secretary of the Vietnamese
Communist Party Do Muoi today began his four-day official visit to
Myanmar to further consolidate the friendly ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Do Muoi's entourage includes Phan Van Khai, member of the
Political Bureau of the Vietnamese Communist Party and Deputy
Prime Minister, Foreign Minister Nguyen Manh Cam and Minister of
Agriculture and Rural Development Nguyen Cong Tan.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Myanmar State Law and Order Restoration Council
 (SLORC) Senior-General Than Shwe, SLORC Vice-Chairman General
Maung Aye and other high ranking officials greeted Do Muoi at the
Yangon International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Do Muoi is scheduled to call on Than Shwe later today and hold
discussions on bilateral ties of friendship and cooperation as
well as regional issues.
</P>
<P>
It was the second visit to Myanmar by a Vietnamese leader in
three years since Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet visited the country
in May 1994.
</P>
<P>
During Vo Van Kiet's visit to Myanmar, the two countries signed
three agreements on trade, tourism and establishment of the Joint
Commission for Bilateral Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Do Muoi last met Myanmar Foreign Minister U Ohn Gyaw in Hanoi
in January this year, during which the second meeting of the
Myanmar-Vietnam Joint Commission for Bilateral Cooperation was
held.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Do Muoi, in receiving newly-accredited Myanmar
Ambassador to Vietnam recently, also expressed Vietnam's support
for Myanmar's bid for membership of ASEAN (the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations), saying that Myanmar's accession to ASEAN
would contribute to peace, stability and development in the region
and the rest of the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
