<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Foreign Trade Up in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Both imports and exports in Macao
increased in the first quarter of the year, with trade deficit
also increasing.
</P>
<P>
Latest figures released by the Macao Census and Statistics
Department show that the export value for the first three months
reached 3.4 billion patacas (about 430 million US dollars), up
16.6 percent from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The imports hit 3.6 billion patacas (about 455.6 million
dollars), up 6.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the trade deficit was recorded at 257 million
patacas (about 32.5 million dollars), up 50.5 percent from the
first three months last year.
</P>
<P>
Textile and garment products, whose value accounted for 83.6
percent all exports, rose 27.7 percent in the first quarter. The
exports of non-textile products, mainly machine and equipment,
footwear and cement, dropped 19.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
About 75.8 percent of Macao exports went to the United States
and the European Union nations. Exports to both places increased
more than 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Macao bought 0.2 percent more consumer's goods, 7.8
percent more semi-finished goods and raw materials, 6.1 percent
more fuel and lubricative oil and 16.1 percent capital goods.
</P>
<P>
The main import market for Macao buyers focuses on the
Asian-Pacific region. Imports from the Chinese mainland, Taiwan
and the EU increased while those from South Korea, Hong Kong,
Japan and Australia dropped in the first quarter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Taliban Forces Mass Around Dostum's Stronghold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 22 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to stop Taliban's
advance, Afghanistan's anti-Taliban alliance was massing their
fighters around Mazar-e-Sharif, the stronghold of Uzbek warlord
Rashid Dostum, about 300 kilometers northwest of Kabul, reports
reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
Ousted Afghan president Burhanuddin Rabbani and his former
military chief, Ahamd Masood, have sent a number of their soldiers
to Mazar-e-Sharif to help Dostum defend the city against an
expected Taliban's assault in the coming days, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Sources in Mazar-e-Sharif claimed over 2,000 men were flown
there from Masood-controlled Taloqan, capital of Takhar province
bordering Tajikistan, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Taliban forces have reportedly reached Maimana,
capital of Faryab province in northwestern Afghanistan, to link up
with forces of General Abdul Malik, who staged a strong rebellion
against Dostum early this week.
</P>
<P>
A senior Taliban official was quoted as saying that their
fighters reached Maimana Wednesday morning and were handed over
most of prisoners of war captured by Malik's men two days ago.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, Taliban officials were holding talks
with Malik in Maimana to plan strategies for the future, adding
that the two forces were cooperating and considering joint
military activities.
</P>
<P>
Malik, one of Dostum's most trusted lieutenants, had announced
support for the Taliban after defecting Dostum's camp. He defended
his action by arguing that it aimed at protecting the territorial
integrity and unity of the country.
</P>
<P>
In a last-ditch effort, Dostum was said to have sent a group of
elders to Faryab province for reconciliation with Malik. Sources
in Mazar-e-Sharif said the elders were trying to persuade Malik to
return to Dostum's side by warning him that the Taliban would dump
him once they complete their stronghold of northern Afghanistan.
However, Afghan sources said Malik had rejected Dostum's overtures
and had made it clear he was not commander of its troops.
</P>
</TEXT>
