<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet Approves New Tax Rates to Boost Revenues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet has decided to
increase excise tax rates for nine products in the hope of
bringing in 2.58 billion baht (about 100 million US dollars) in
revenue in the remaining four months of fiscal 1997.
</P>
<P>
The government is under pressure to increase revenue because
expected tax revenue shortfall this year would likely to result in
the first budget deficit in a decade.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting on Wednesday, the cabinet also decided to cut the
proposed 1998 fiscal budget by 26 billion baht (about 1 billion
dollars) to 982 billion baht (37.77 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the cabinet already reduced expenditures for the 1997
fiscal budget by 59 billion baht (2.27 billion dollars) to 925
billion baht (35.58 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Fiscal 1998 begins on October 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Of the nine product categories which face immediately effective
tax rises, two-stroke motorcycles, cars and flashlight batteries,
and marble and granite, all of which are considered to be harmful
to the environment, will be assessed excise taxes of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Up until now they have been free from excise tax.
</P>
<P>
The remaining six items -- soft drinks, chandeliers, perfume,
crystal glassware, horse racetrack entrance fees, and air
conditioners -- would see tax increases ranging from two to seven
percentage points.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
