<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO's Expansion Not to Bring Safety to Europe: Belarus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 21 (Xinhua) -- NATO's eastward expansion will not
bring new safety guarantee to Europe, Belarussian President
Alexander Lukashenko said today.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the first conference of military officers of the
Belarussian armed forces, Lukashenko said if NATO's expansion
became irreversible, his country would take all necessary measures
to minimize possible negative impact arising from it.
</P>
<P>
The Belarussian president hoped the ties between Belarus and
NATO could be set up on the basis of trust, frankness and
partnership.
</P>
<P>
He said the modernized armed forces of Belarus will contribute
to the establishment of such relations.
</P>
<P>
Belarussian Defense Minister Alexandr Chumakov accused NATO of
its obstinate stand on eastward expansion, which he said has
caused unprecedented tension among countries in Europe.
</P>
<P>
He said that Belarussian servicemen should not ignore the
statements of some Western politicians over the redivision of
Europe and deployment of nuclear weapons in new NATO member states.
</P>
<P>
Chumakov disclosed that Belarus has cut the number of its armed
forces from 250,000 to 83,000 over the past five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
