<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albanians to Vote on Restoration of Monarchy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Albanian President Sali Berisha
signed a decree today to hold a referendum on restoring the
monarchy on the same day as nationwide parliamentary elections,
due on June 29.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made following a law passed by the National
Assembly (parliament) on May 13 allowing a referendum on whether
the country should return to a constitutional monarchy or remain a
republic.
</P>
<P>
Albania's King Leka, 58, has been in exile since he was a baby
when his father King Zog fled the country in the face of invading
Italian fascists in 1939.
</P>
<P>
He returned to the country in April after two months of rioting
which followed the collapse of pyramid investment schemes in which
thousands of Albanian families lost their life savings.
</P>
<P>
King Leka, who sees himself as a unifying factor in the
troubled country, met President Berisha on his return and got him
to promise to hold a referendum on the monarchy.
</P>
<P>
However, there is still uncertainty surrounding the
parliamentary elections themselves.
</P>
<P>
The opposition, led by the Socialist Party, the second largest
party in the country, have threatened to boycott the elections,
saying a new draft election law passed by the parliament on May 16
favored Berisha's ruling Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Party and many other parties boycotted the vote
on the law and demanded amendments.
</P>
<P>
After several rounds of negotiations, differences still exist
between the Democratic Party and other parties on the revision of
the election law.
</P>
<P>
Although opposition leaders warned on Wednesday of possible
manipulation and demanded strict monitoring of the vote, it was
still not clear if the opposition would take part.
</P>
<P>
After day-long talks with the parties and government, Prime
Minister Bashkim Fino on Wednesday sent a letter to Franz
Vranitzky, the special envoy to Albania from the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), asking for
international monitors to oversee the whole electoral process,
reports said.
</P>
<P>
"The final solution to ensure free, fair and equal elections
where all would participate and not contest the result, would be to
guarantee intensive monitoring of all levels of the electoral
process," he said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
Fatos Nano, leader of the Socialists, said full monitoring
would be enough to persuade his party to stand in the elections,
even under the current law, the reports added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
