<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Breed 42 Giant Pandas by Artificial Insemination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have successfully bred
42 giant pandas by artificial insemination at a research centre in
China's southwestern province of Sichuan, where about 80 percent
of the endangered species inhabit.
</P>
<P>
The Chengdu Giant Pandas Reproduction Research Base started
breeding the giant pandas by artificial insemination in 1980 and have
successfully made 28 giant pandas pregnant, producing 48 pandas.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-three of the artificially-bred giant pandas have
survived and the rest died before they reached six months old.
</P>
<P>
The breeding base, located in the northern suburbs of Chengdu
and occupying an area of over 30 hectares, imitates the natural
habitat.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, two dozen pandas live at the breeding base,
which is the only research institute of giant panda reproduction
in China.
</P>
<P>
Giant pandas normally get pregnant once a year and produce one
or two babies at each birth.
</P>
<P>
"The female giant pandas always show indifference and contempt
to the approaching male giant pandas during the mating season," a
researcher at the breeding centre said.
</P>
<P>
"So it's very difficult to have them make love and get pregnant
naturally," he said, adding that "only 10 percent of the giant
pandas are able to mate naturally."
</P>
<P>
Researchers at the breeding base are studying techniques of
enhancing the sexual desire and performance, improving the
survival rate of baby pandas, and artificial insemination,
according to researchers from the institute.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila's Exit From IMF Program Seen Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government may ask
for the postponement of the country's exit from the International
Monetary Fund's (IMF's) three-year extended fund facility (EFF)
program, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Gabriel Singson, governor of the Central Bank of the
Philippines, admitted Wednesday that the government may be
compelled to do so due to the delay in the passage of the
remaining portion of the country's Comprehensive Tax Reform
Program.
</P>
<P>
The completion of the country's tax reform program is part of
the structural reforms pledged under the IMF's three year EFF
program.
</P>
<P>
The IMF Executive Board is set to approve the country's
graduation from the EFF program before the program's expiration by
June 23 this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the Philippine Congress up to now has yet to pass the
remaining portion of the tax package. Congress goes on recess on
June 5 and will resume sessions in July, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But Singson did not say whether the government would
renegotiate a new deadline to complete the tax reform program.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Singson has raised the possibility that the
country may extend the program by another six months if the tax
reform would not be completed by the time of the scheduled exit,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has been under the IMF's conditional lending
for 35 years under 23 loan programs. The current program under the
IMF's EFF, often dubbed the country's exit program, has been in
place since June 1994.
</P>
<P>
The EFF program provided the country some 474.5 million US
dollars in special drawing rights to support the economic and
financial program of the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Neolithic Relics Found in Shandong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Stone, pottery, and shellware have
been unearthed from a neolithic site in Lingxian county in east
China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
Found in the old course of the Yellow River, the relics include
a stone knife, an axe, a sickle, deer horns, shell sickles, and
pottery textile wheels.
</P>
<P>
The knife and sickle, with only their upper half remaining,
were made of black stone. The pottery textile wheel, with a
diameter of 5.2 cm, has a eight-mm-round hole.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists say that the find will contribute to the
study of the origin of civilization along the Yellow River, which
is regarded as a cradle of Chinese civilization.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
