<HEADLINE> Oriental Silk Festival Attracts 82 Million US Dollars In Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 82 million US dollars in
deals were contracted during the week-long festival, half of which
accounted for by pledged intention, at the Fifth Dandong Oriental
Silk Festival closed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The festival drew participants of more than 30 countries and
regions into this year's fair, according to today's "China
Daily".
</P>
<P>
The country's biggest border city in northeast China's Liaoning
province, Dandong is home to one quarter of silkworm production
worldwide and holds a 70 percent share of the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony to mark the construction of an industrial park was
also held at the fair between Dandong and Inchon city in Republic
of Korea (ROK).
</P>
<P>
Covering 448,000 square meters, the park is to be finished by
Inchon of ROK in the Dandong Border Economic Cooperation
Zone. With 5.4 million US dollars capital injected into the area,
the zone is expected to create more than 12,000 opportunities for
local employees.
</P>
<P>
More than 40,000 workers are involved in the silk business,
which once held 40 percent of the city's total industry
output. Liu Tinyao, mayor of Dandong said that his "silk city" has
used overseas funds over the past several years to develop
electronics, auto parts, chemical fibres and paper-making, the
paper says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Efforts to Be Made to Boost Thai Shrimp Export to EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Agriculture Ministry will
coordinate with the European Union (EU) to tackle environmental
problems resulting from shrimp farming to boost Thai shrimp export
to EU countries, according to a Thai senior official.
</P>
<P>
Thai senior officials will meet their EU counterparts in
Brussels from June 4-5 to discuss the matter, Adisak Sreesunpagit,
assistant agriculture permanent secretary, was quoted today by
local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We will persuade the EU to sell environment technology, such
as waste water treatment facility, to Thai shrimp farmers," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Adisak said Thai delegates would also propose to the EU to set
up a standardization center in Thailand which would inspect and
certify the quality of goods before they are shipped to EU
countries.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is among the top ten exporters of aquatic products,
especially farmed shrimp, to EU countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
