</P>
<P>
-- China has welcomed the Commonwealth of the Bahamas's
severing of "diplomatic ties" with Taiwan and deciding to
establish diplomatic ties with the People's Republic of China,
said a Foreign Ministry spokesman here yesterday.
</P>
<P>
-- China's central economic and financial authorities has
issued a regulation to ban state-owned enterprises and listed
companies from stock speculation, in an effort to bring into play
the function of the socialist stock market and maintain a normal
market order.
</P>
<P>
It required that the state-owned enterprises should not be
involved in stock speculation or provide funds for other
institutions to speculate in stocks, nor should they use money
loaned from state banks to purchase stocks.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China stands firm in its opposition to trade protectionism
and supports the role played by the World Trade Organization in
international economy and trade, said Chinese vice-premier Li
Lanqing yesterday at the 30th International General Meeting of the
Pacific Basin Economic Council meeting held in Manila.
</P>
<P>
"China needs WTO, and WTO needs China. Without China, the World
Trade Organization can not fully exert its influence," he said.
</P>
<P>
-- Twenty-one provinces across the country reported a total of
369 new HIV positive AIDS cases during the first three months of
this year, the Chinese Ministry of Public Health announced
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The new cases bring the total number of HIV/AIDS patients to
6,359. 
