<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Supports Creation of Palestinian State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican Foreign Minister
Fernando Naranjo reiterated today his country's support for the
creation of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Naranjo said this at a press conference one day before former
Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres is due to arrive in Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica was the first country to open its embassy in
Jerusalem, against the orders of the United States, and has always
maintained particularly close relations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Naranjo reaffirmed the good relations between the two countries
but said that his government supports the U.N. resolution that
agreed on the creation of an Israel state as well as a Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica's Foreign Ministry has also decided to grant aid to
Palestinian authorities and will send a medical delegation to
Palestinian territory in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
Naranjo stated that his country has no objection whatsoever to
the establishment of a Palestinian office here.
</P>
<P>
"We are concerned about the policy of Jewish settlements in
east Jerusalem," added the foreign minister, "because it
jeopardizes the peace process in the region."
</P>
<P>
"We have conveyed our concern to Israel but that does not mean
that we are no longer in good relations or that we are criticizing
them," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
