<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (97-98) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the Basic
Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (97-98) in a
question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: Who has the power to interpret the Basic Law?
</P>
<P>
Answer: The power of interpretation of the Basic Law is vested
in the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The Standing Committee of the NPC will authorize the courts of
the Hong Kong SAR to interpret on their own, in adjudicating
cases, the provisions of the Basic Law which are within the limits
of the autonomy of the region.
</P>
<P>
The courts of the Hong Kong SAR may also interpret other
provisions of the Basic Law in adjudicating cases.
</P>
<P>
However, if disputes should arise concerning interpretations of
the courts of the Hong Kong SAR, the power to render final
arbitration goes to the Standing Committee of the NPC.
</P>
<P>
If disputes should arise concerning provisions outside the
limits of the autonomy of the Hong Kong SAR, interpretations of
the Standing Committee of the NPC shall be final.
</P>
<P>
The Standing Committee of the NPC will consult its Committee
for the Basic Law of the Hong Kong SAR before giving an
interpretation of the Basic Law provisions.
</P>
<P>
Question: What if existing Hong Kong laws contravene the Basic
Law?
</P>
<P>
Answer: The Basic Law is the fundamental legal code of the Hong
Kong SAR. Any existing local laws that contravene it will lose
their validity after July 1, 1997. Such laws may be amended in
accordance with procedures as prescribed by the Basic Law to make
them conform to the Basic Law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
