<HEADLINE> Panama, US Try To Eliminate And Prevent Borer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A Panama-U.S. Commission has
met and decided to execute a program on eradication and prevention
of the borer insect on the Panamanian territory.
</P>
<P>
The objective of this commission is to protect livestock which,
in turn, benefits wildlife and the health of human beings, said
Michael Dunn, U.S. undersecretary of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The three-year program, administered by the U.S. Department of
Agriculture's Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service, will
have an investment of 40 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Panama will contribute 15 percent of that amount and the United
States the remainder, said Carlos Sousa Lennox, Panama's
Agricultural Development Minister.
</P>
<P>
The program will create 200 jobs of which 60 percent will be
professionals and the rest administrative employees and operators,
he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Dunn, the eradication of the borer in the United
States has benefited cattle ranchers to the sum of about 500
million dollars per year.
</P>
<P>
In Mexico and Central America the eradication has helped to
save 341 million dollars per year.
</P>
<P>
The borer causes heavy losses every year in southern United
States because it affected cattle herds and wildlife. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
