<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China reports Rise in AIDS Incidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-one provinces in China
reported a total of 369 new HIV positive AIDS cases during the
first three months of this year, today's China Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
Quoting figures from the Ministry of Public Health, it
says that the new cases bring the total number of HIV/AIDS
patients in the country to 6,359.
</P>
<P>
China is still among those nations with a low rate of HIV/AIDS,
says the report. Its occurrence, however, has expanded rapidly in
some parts of the country, and its rampant incidence in some
neighboring countries poses a threat to China, Vice-Minister of
public Health Yin Dakui said at the opening session of a National
Symposium on AIDS Control yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The report quotes Yin as saying that China will establish a
National Center for AIDS Control to provide technical guidance for
the work, as well as a national laboratory base to do research
work on HIV/AIDS control and treatment.
</P>
<P>
He added the country has completed work in fields such as
publicity and education, expanding surveillance and the testing of
blood products.
</P>
<P>
China's central government has promulgated several regulations
focusing on HIV/AIDS control. The ministry has established 60
surveillance spots as bases for research. The Chinese Academy of
Preventive Medicine, in cooperation with the Yunnan Anti-Epidemic
Station, has successfully separated the major strain of virus from
HIV carriers in Yunnan province and is working on a
second-generation vaccine.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Research Institute of Traditional Chinese Medicine
has developed seven groups of herbal medicines to treat HIV/AIDS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
