<HEADLINE> Australia's 10 Billion Dollar Gas Project to Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Two Australian companies have
planned a 10 billion Australian dollar (7.76 billion US dollar)
gas project near Darwin to rival the North West Shelf operation
and cement Australia as the dominant energy supplier to Asia.
</P>
<P>
The project near Darwin, a coastal city in northern Australia,
could begin exporting liquefied natural gas by 2005 if an 18-month
feasibility study leads to the development, local newspapers
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The two companies, Shell Australia and Woodside Petroleum Ltd,
proposed to build a liquefied natural gas plant to produce 7.5
million tons of liquefied natural gas a year, which would generate
annual export revenue of about 1.5 billion Australian dollars
(1.155 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The target markets include Japan, South Korea, China and
Thailand.  
