<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Says NATO-Russia Accord Not to Limit NATO's Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The document that the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) and Russia will sign in Paris
next week will not limit the alliance's freedom of action, a
senior U.S. official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters about President Bill Clinton's trip to
Europe next week, Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott said
that the so-called NATO-Russia Founding Act would not tie the
alliance's hands when involving in any conflicts.
</P>
<P>
According to the Founding Act, NATO and Russia will form a
permanent joint council that will make decisions on the basis of
consensus.
</P>
<P>
"The absence of a consensus in the NATO-Russia joint council
does not in any way affect the freedom of action, the freedom of
decision, either of NATO and ... or of Russia," Talbott said.
</P>
<P>
The North Atlantic Council, NATO's policy-making body, "stands
on its own and will continue to stand its own," he added.
</P>
<P>
Sandy Berger, the national security advisor, also briefed
reporters and said that if NATO's decision could be vetoed by
Russia, it would be proceeding with its eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Talbott indicated that the pledges that NATO made
on the deployment of nuclear weapons and substantial troops in the
new member states are "reassertions of NATO's own policy" and not
"negotiated limits on NATO's freedom of action."
</P>
<P>
"The alliance reserves the unilateral right to reassess the
security environment at any time, and if it felt there was a new
challenge, to change deployments accordingly," he added.
</P>
<P>
NATO promised Russia, which strongly opposes to the military
bloc's enlargement, that it would not deploy nuclear arms nor
substantial combat forces on the territories of the new member
countries after the alliance expands into the Eastern and Central
Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Gold Going To Market This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- China mined 9.9 tons of gold last
month, bringing combined production in the first four months of
the year to 35 tons, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The production represents 35 percent of the full output planned
for 1997 and an increase of 20 percent over the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
The paper quotes an official from the production division of
the Gold Bureau under the Ministry of Metallurgical Industry as
saying that gold production will surpass its goal of 100 tons set
by the central government.
</P>
<P>
China decided to reduce the purchase price of gold by 5 percent
to six percent early this year in an effort to better integrate
the domestic gold price with the international price.
</P>
<P>
The price was reduced to just over 10.84 US dollars per gram
from 11.45 US dollars per gram. The current price is approximately
equivalent to 375 US dollars per ounce.
</P>
<P>
China will invest 120 million US dollars in the construction of
new facilities to mine and process an additional 3.75 tons of gold
in 1997, officials from the bureau said early this year.
</P>
<P>
Another 72.3 million US dollars will be used for technical
renovations which will help increase annual capacity by another
3.5 tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
