<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine, Poland Formally Bury Historical Feud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma and
his visiting Polish counterpart Alexander Kwasniewski signed a
joint communique here on Wednesday, officially ending historical
feud between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference after the signing ceremony, Kuchma said
the unhappy past would never cast shadow on the Ukrainian and
Polish peoples at present as well as in the future.
</P>
<P>
The joint communique, entitled "Toward Harmony and Unity," would
turn over the dark pages of the Ukrainian-Polish relations, Kuchma
added.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine was occupied by Poland between 14th-16th century before
it integrated with Russia at the end of the 16th century.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine formed its first republic when it declared independence
in 1918 from the Austrian-Hungarian Empire after World War
I. Eight months later, however, the Ukrainian National Republic
was overthrown by its Polish minorities who were backed by Poland.
</P>
<P>
The relations between the two countries began to warm up after
Ukraine became independent from the former Soviet Union in
1991. Poland was the first to recognize its independence. Now, the
two countries hope to join hands in a bid to have a louder voice
on European affairs.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski, who arrived in Kiev accompanied by 60 businessmen
on Tuesday for a three-day visit, will also hold talks with
Ukrainian Prime Minister Pavlo Lazarenko, parliamentary speaker
Alexandre Moroz to discuss economic issues.
</P>
<P>
Five agreements are expected to be signed on cooperation in
health, finance, culture, science and education.
</P>
<P>
Some 700 Polish companies are operational in Ukraine, and the
trade between the two countries totalled over one billion
U.S. dollars in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaraguans to Be Evacuated due to Volcano Eruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A state of alert was declared today
in this northwestern state of Nicaragua because of the eruption of
the San Cristobal volcano and thousands of people there have begun
to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
The 1,745-meter high volcano, which is the highest and most
dangerous one in Nicaragua, began to spew ashes and gravel on May
19 over the city of Chinandega located 15 kilometers west of the
volcano.
</P>
<P>
Some 6,000 people who live on the skirts of the volcano will
have to be evacuated because of the increase of the volcanic
activity.
</P>
<P>
The Nicaraguan Institute of Territorial Studies (INETER) is
following the volcanic activity closely and has sent three groups
of geologists and volcanologists to San Cristobal to evaluate the
situation.
</P>
<P>
Experts did not rule out the eruption of lava. Late Tuesday
afternoon, a mushroom of white smoke covered the state municipal
hall and loud explosions inside the crater could be heard.
</P>
<P>
INETER Director Luis Munoz Valdes said that apart from the
evacuation of people who live in the hamlets close to the volcano,
security measures will also be taken for the nearly 118,000
Chinandega residents.
</P>
<P>
According to the institute, the first record of an eruption of
the volcano occurred in 1883. Since then, there have been 12
major eruptions, the last one occurring in 1977. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
