<HEADLINE> Uruguayan President Ends Visit to Venezuela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Uruguayan President Julio Maria
Sanguinetti left today for the United States, after concluding an
official visit to Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day stay, Sanguinetti held talks with his
Venezuelan counterpart, Rafael Caldera, and signed several
agreements including a joint declaration, an extradition treaty
and an agreement on mutual promotion and protection of investments.
</P>
<P>
In the joint declaration, Sanguinetti and Caldera said they
were happy with the progress made in trade cooperation, which,
they said, "serves as a stimulus to continue exploring to the
utmost the potential for trade that exists between both countries."
</P>
<P>
The two presidents underlined the importance of measures aimed
at promoting bilateral trade and investment, which constitute the
most effective means for strengthening economic relations.
</P>
<P>
They identified the energy sector as a priority for joint
development and agreed on the importance of forming a strategic
association on oil issues.
</P>
<P>
Sanguinetti also supported Venezuela's bid to join the
four-nation Southern Common Market (Mercosur) which groups
Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay and Paraguay. Chile and Bolivia are
associate members.
</P>
<P>
The two governments also signed a treaty over mutual legal
assistance in penal matters and a memorandum of understanding for
cooperation in education. 
</P>
