<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Confident to Meet Deficit Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Italian State Comptroller General
Andrea Monorchio said today that he was confident that Italy will
meet its target of bringing the budget deficit to three percent of
the gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the sidelines of a conference organized by the
State Accounting Office, Monorchio said "I am convinced that by
the end of the year the target will be met."
</P>
<P>
Monorchio also focused on welfare reforms and noted that the
aging population will become a serious problem for the country.
Between the years 1994 and 2004, Italy's senior citizens will
increase by 173 percent and the number of young people will fall
by 20 percent, Monorchio said.
</P>
<P>
On the country's financial conditions, Monorchio said Italy is
the only industrial country in the world to boast a primary
surplus of sixty trillion lire (about 36.1 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, debt hit 123 trillion lire (74.1 billion
dollars) in 1996 and should be brought down to 60 trillion lire,
Monorchio said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
