<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Adopts Convention on International Watercourses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The UN General Assembly
today adopted a Convention on the Law of the Non-Navigational Uses
of International Watercourses aimed at guiding states and regional
economic integration organizations to become parties to it.
</P>
<P>
The resolution to which the convention was attached was adopted
by 103 votes in favor to 3 against (Burundi, China and Turkey)
with 27 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
The 37-article International Watercourses Convention and its
14-article annex governs the non-navigational uses of
international watercourses, as well as measures to protect,
preserve and manage them.
</P>
<P>
Viewed as a framework convention, it addresses such issues as
flood control, water quality, erosion, sedimentation, saltwater
intrusion and living resources.
</P>
<P>
The convention is to be opened for signature today and remain
open until 20 May 2000. It will enter into force 90 days after is
has been ratified by 35 signatories.
</P>
<P>
The states who vote against or abstained drew attention to a
lack of consensus on several of its provisions, such as those
governing dispute settlement, lack of balance in its provisions
between the rights and obligations of the upstream and downstream
states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Bosnian Parties Responsible For Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian parties should be
ultimately responsible for implementing the Dayton peace accords,
said U.S. president Bill Clinton in a letter published on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The letter was a reply to a Chicago-based Bosnian refugee
association about the U.S. stance on Bosnia and published by the
Sarajevan daily Oslobodjenje.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said in the letter that "The United States continues to
work in concert with others in the international community to
encourage the parties to fulfill their commitments under the
Dayton Peace Agreement and to build on the gains achieved since
December 1995".
</P>
<P>
He said that the mission of Nato-led Stablization Force (SFOR)
should be completed by June of next year and that conditions can be
established for maintaining stability and security without an
foreign military presence.
</P>
<P>
"It remains in the U.S. national interest to help bring peace
to Bosnia -- not only for humanitarian reasons, but to reduce the
threats to general security and stability in Europe," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Although the United States and its allies can provide the
opportunity for bringing about peace, "it is they who are
ultimately responsible for implementing the peace agreement",
Clinton added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CDB Accepts China's Membership Application </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TORONTO, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The board of governors of the
Caribbean Development Bank (CDB) today accepted China's
application to join the organization as a non-regional,
non-borrowing member country.
</P>
<P>
Today's formal approval has taken much closer to the point of
completion the process which began on September 16, 1993, when
China submitted its application, according a CDB press release.
</P>
<P>
China's admission is "an important, historic development" for
the 28-year-old organization, said Don Boudria, chairman of the
meeting and Canadian minister for international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by Xinhua, a Chinese official at the meeting said
that the Chinese government attaches great importance to its
cooperation with the Caribbean region and is looking forward to a
closer cooperation with the bank.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the political, economic and trade ties between
China and the Caribbean region will be further strengthened" with
China's admission into the bank, the official noted.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1969, CDB is a major financer of infrastructure and
social sector development projects and promotes regional
integration in the Caribbean community.
</P>
<P>
Currently it is composed of 17 regional borrowing members,
three regional non-borrowing members and five non-regional
members.
</P>
<P>
CDB's board of governors are gathering here for the two-day
27th annual meeting. This is the first time that CDB has held its
annual meetings outside the Caribbean region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0324 </DOCNO>
