<HEADLINE> House Speaker Urges Building Drug-Free America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Newt Gingrich, the speaker of
the U.S. House of Representatives, on Wednesday, called on the
nation's mayors to contribute to building a drug-free America by
2001.
</P>
<P>
"We would be a different country" if that were to happen,
Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich also said television networks could afford to help by
donating air time.
</P>
<P>
"If you could eliminate the drug problem from most
neighborhoods and... from most schools, you've eliminated a very
high percentage of drug abuse, a very high percentage of spousal
abuse," Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich made his remarks at a meeting where a task force of
the U.S. Conference of Mayors, local police chiefs and prosecutors
presented Congress with their blueprint for combating the
nation's drug epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which reflects the government's anti-drug policy,
urges greater community involvement with youngsters. It also
prescribes increased prevention and treatment, coupled with strict
law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich said the United States has the resources to "destroy
the drug culture" if it so desires, and should use them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
