<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Announces 1998 Production Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Boeing Commercial Airplane Group
of the U.S. today announced production rate changes on a number of
its airplane models.
</P>
<P>
The rate changes, which take effect in 1998, will result in a
production rate of 43 airplanes per month by the second quarter of
that year.
</P>
<P>
Boeing, the world's No. 1 producer of commercial jets,
announced last December that the company's monthly production
would reach a record 40 airplanes by the fourth quarter of this
year. The previous record of 39.5 airplanes per month was reached
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The new production rates will be set as follows: By the second
quarter of 1998, production of the 737 will be 24 airplanes per
month. That number includes a combination of the Next-Generation
and current model 737s. In the second quarter of 1998, the 747
rate will increase from four airplanes per month to five. The 777
rate will go from seven airplanes per month to five beginning in
March 1998. Production of the 757 will increase from four to five
airplanes in the second quarter of 1998. Production of the 767 is
currently expected to remain at four airplanes per month
throughout 1998.
</P>
<P>
The company also has announced that in 1997 it is expected to
deliver approximately 340 airplanes of all models.
</P>
<P>
In its recently issued 20-year assessment of worldwide market,
Boeing forecast air passenger traffic growth of 4.9 percent a year
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
To meet that growth and replace aging aircraft, the report
noted that the world's airlines are expected to add about 16,160
airplanes to their fleets, worth more than 1.1 trillion U.S.
dollars, during that same time period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks on Wall Street Edge Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Technology shares on Wall Street
rose today, but blue-chip shares pulled back as interest rates
jumped in the bond market.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average lost 12.77 points to
7,290.69, recovering from a 64-point drop.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by more than a 5-to-4 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume totaling 537.05
million shares much more than the 447.17 million in the previous
session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 2.27 to 839.39, and
the NYSE's composite index fell 0.99 to 436.21. Both big-company
measures flirted with record highs in the morning before turning
lower.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 9.87 to 1,373.75, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index rose 1.32 to 592.08.
</P>
<P>
Bonds fell after the Commerce Department reported that the U.S.
trade deficit narrowed dramatically in March to 8.5 billion U.S.
dollars as U.S. exports rose to a second consecutive monthly
record.
</P>
<P>
The surprisingly robust data spurred worries that economic
growth was even quicker in the first quarter than the 5.6 percent
rate recently reported. That advance in the gross domestic product
was the fastest in nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
As bond prices fell today, the yield on the 30-year Treasury
bond rose to 6.98 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
