<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Shares up on Unchanged US Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Leading stock markets in Europe
recovered from Tuesday's losses and ended higher Wednesday as the
US central bank decided to leave US interest rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
British shares in London opened strongly today but came back
from session highs later in the day as Wall Street tempered its
early advance, with the FTSE 100 index up 34.5 points at 4,642.0.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the market was relieved at the US Federal
Reserve's decision not to raise US rates and weaker-than-expected
UK money supply data for April also boosted stock prices.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares, which had suffered heavy losses
Tuesday, today made the greatest advance and held on their early
gains in the wake of a decision to hold US interest rates, with
the DAX-30 index closed the session 52.66 points higher at
3,596.09.
</P>
<P>
Supported by the interest rates news from the US, the Paris
bourse had recovered all of its losses suffered on Tuesday and had
climbed to the 2,800-level once again earlier in the day before
drifting back amid profit-taking and ending up 35.24 points at
2,786.35.
</P>
<P>
Sentiment was expected to remain cautious ahead of Sunday's
vote in the parliamentary election.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index of leading British shares closed up
34.5 points at 4,642.0. The Frankfurt DAX-30 index ended 52.66
points higher at 3,596.09. In Paris, the CAC-40 index finished
35.24 points stronger at 2,786.35. 
</P>
</TEXT>
