<HEADLINE> China Stresses Sovereignty of Watercourse State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A state had indisputable
sovereignty over the watercourse which flowed through its
territory, a Chinese representative said at the UN General
Assembly here today.
</P>
<P>
Explaining China's position on vote against the resolution to
which the Convention on Non-Navigational Uses of International
Watercourses was attached, China's representative Gao Feng pointed
out there were obvious drawbacks in the draft convention.
</P>
<P>
First, it failed to reflect general agreement among all
countries, and a number of states had major reservations regarding
its main provisions. Secondly, the text did not reflect the
principle of the territorial sovereignty of a watercourse state.
Such a state had indisputable sovereignty over a watercourse which
flowed through its territory.
</P>
<P>
There was also imbalance between the rights and obligations of
the upstream and downstream states, he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, China could not support provisions on the mandatory
settlement of disputes in the international convention on
watercourses, as the provisions went against the principles set
out in the United Nations Charter, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Government favored the settlement of all disputes
through peaceful negotiations, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly today adopted a resolution on the
37-article convention with 103 votes in favor, three against and
27 abstentions. Voting against were China, turkey and Burundi
while Argentina, Egypt, France, India, Pakistan were among those
abstaining.
</P>
<P>
The resolution asks UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan to open the
convention for signature. The convention will enter into force 90
days after it has been ratified by 35 signatories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
