<DOCNO> XIE19970522.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Rises on Trade Data and Comments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar rose broadly
Wednesday after the government reported an unexpected shrinkage in
the monthly trade deficit and comments from a senior German
central banker who preferred a stable dollar.
</P>
<P>
In New York, the dollar settled at 114.18 yen, up from 113.04
yen Tuesday. The dollar cost 1.6946 marks, up from 1.6823. The
pound cost 1.6450 U.S. dollars, down from 1.6570 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The main force helping the dollar was the Commerce Department
report that the March trade deficit narrowed sharply to 8.5
billion U.S. dollars due largely to record export sales. Many
traders had been expecting the deficit to widen.
</P>
<P>
The report reduced fears that the dollar's recent strength has
made U.S. goods too expensive.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Tuesday:
1.4085 Swiss francs, up from 1.3905; 5.7075 French francs, up from
5.6675; 1,667.25 Italian lire, up from 1,656.00; 1.3672 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.3664. 
</P>
</TEXT>
